CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old right-handed female with past history of epilepsy, bipolar disease, now with generalized weakness, abdominal pain, and starting spells.

MEDICATIONS: Protonix, amoxicillin, Clarithromycin, diazepam, depakote, Zoloft, Lovenox, Tylenol, Percocet, Ceftriaxone

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation is not performed, but photic simulation was completed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of excess beta and theta. Brief drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.

HR: 84 bpm

IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess beta and theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The excess beta and theta may be associated with medications used to treat this patient's other medical conditions. If epilepsy is an important consideration a follow-up study may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old woman with PRES syndrome, eclampsia, admitted with 2 seizures and a past history of a single childhood seizure, now with blood
pressure under control and resolving proteinuria.

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Labetalol, ASA

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is quite drowsy, but coherent.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates an intermittent, somewhat slow pattern. Bursts of rhythmic frontally predominantly delta are observed. In addition, there are occasional bursts of slower more arrhythmic delta activity in the occipital regions. As the patient transitions into stage I sleep, vertex waves are observed. Photic stimulation is performed while she is relatively drowsy, but she does alert and there is brief driving response.

HR: 66 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background much slower than expected for age.
2. FIRDA.
3. Occasional occipitally predominant delta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. In this individual who appears to be improving clinically, a followup study looking at her improvement over time may be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male with status epilepticus earlier this morning status post 10 mg of Ativan, Dilantin, and Keppra. History of cervical myelopathy. Intubated and paralyzed prior to the EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan, Etomidate, Fentanyl, Versed, ROCURONIUM
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is starting to emerge from paralysis and demonstrates stiffening and movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is a bit quieter. Activity demonstrates a slow pattern with some rhythmic mixed theta and delta on the left with a lower voltage, slower, a bit more suppressed pattern on the right, particularly in the temporal regions.
Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle as well as alpha and theta frequency activity. During the EEG, the patient starts to wake up, move around, and cough. After this, there is a more alert pattern with more theta frequency and alpha frequency activity from the left, but the right remains quite slow. By the end of the record in this very sharply contoured record, there was a suggestion of underlying sharp activity versus part of the fast activity at F3. In addition, more sharply contoured slowing is seen at T4-T6.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere.
2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function as would be expected following the use of sedative, hypnotic medications. The focal slowing and rare sharp waves on the right are compatible with past right temporal hemorrhage. Additional evaluation of this patient's cerebral function may be needed. Ongoing EEG monitoring was undertaken to make sure no additional seizures occurred.

CLINICAL HISTORY: A 53-year-old male found unresponsive, hypothermic, hyperglycemic coma with acute brain stem syndrome.

MEDICATIONS: Protonix, vancomycin, Xanax and others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is stimulated during the EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Some sections of the record demonstrate a slow pattern almost discontinuous with more 1-2 hertz delta and left theta. As the recording continues, the discontinuity decreases and there is more rhythmic theta. There are a handful of triphasic waves observed.

Stimulation of the patient is performed in the later sections of the record and stimulation including checking the gag demonstrate nice increase in reactivity and increase in theta and the presence of cranial nerve signs.

Heart rate 70 to 112 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to marked background slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG demonstrates a dynamic pattern with an improvement in the background over time as might be seen in the context of a toxic or metabolic insult. By the close of the record, the background is unpathologically slow. Additional clinical evaluation may be appropriate. No epileptiform features were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 33 year old male with refractory epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Lamictal, ZONISAMIDE, Buspar, Folate Acid, Seroquel, Diazepam,
Clorazepate, Valium
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a markedly abnormal pattern lacking in the Typical wave forms of an awake adult. It is relatively low voltage and featureless with frequent high amplitude slow spike and wave activity of approximately 2-3 Hz. In addition, there is predominant polyspike activity, focal epileptiform activity in the right hemisphere, frontal central, and some isolated discharges from the left. There is likely 1 seizure in this EEG during photic stimulation, but after the 7 Hz stimulation concludes when the Patient has a burst of alpha frequency activity on the right with head turning to the left.
HR: 96bpm
IMPRESSION: markedly ABNORMAL EEG due to:
1. Absence of normal wave forms for an adult of this age.
2. High amplitude spike and wave activity and polyspike and wave activity.
3. Focal activity more prominent on the right, but seen independently from the left.
4. Seizure in right
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are seen In Lennox-Gastaut type syndrome and are quite typical. Is focal activity and in this EEG, at least, it is a bit more prominent on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old female with epilepsy, seizure free for 2 years, follow
up EEG.

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is 9.9 alpha rhythm. There
seems to be a breech rhythm with accentuation of amplitude in the right occipital region.
Vertex waves and POSTS are noted in stage 1 sleep with spindles in stage 2 sleep,
with right occipital delta. Hyperventilation increases the amplitude. Photic stimulation
elicits driving.

HR: 80 bpm

IMPRESSION: Very mild abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal delta on right occipital lesion.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG did not identity any sharp waves or spikes. The
focal delta in amplitude and asymmetry can be seen in the context of a structural
abnormality. Clinical correlation is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old male with history of seizures. Evaluate post Code for anoxic encephalopathy; date of anoxia not recorded.

MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital, Dilantin, Depakote, Valproate Acid, Zosyn, Midazolam, Amiodarone, Dopamine, Norepinephrine, Dobutamine, Vasopressin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive. This was a 4-hour EEG study.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a low voltage pattern with intermittent theta and scant amounts of delta. Muscle artifact is observed. No myoclonus is noted. Occasional very subtle frontal sharp wave contoured theta waves are observed. As the muscle artifact drops out in the background, a discontinuous pattern is observed.

HR: 120 bpm.
IMPRESSION: This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Replacement of normal background with a pattern of relatively invariant, arrhythmic theta delta.
2. Intermittent discontinuity.
3. Absence of reactivity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing demonstrates some positive but some negative findings for a patient status post significant anoxic injury. To put this in appropriate clinical context, the day of the anoxic injury should be documented. No epileptiform features were observed and no clinical seizures were noted. Of note, the background demonstrates less muscle and more discontinuity in the later portions of this 4-hour, critical care bedside recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 65 year old male with encephalopathy and possible seizures, history of hypertension, heart failure, and ART.

MEDICATIONS: Lasix, Synthroid, Lipitor, Synthroid, KCL, Glyburide, Lopressor

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Central new activity is identified. There are occasional bursts of generalized delta and a handful of bursts which are a little asynchronous, more prominent from the left. The vast majority of the record, however, is well-organized. Features of drowsiness include slowing of the background with slow rolling eye movements.

HR: 96 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A handful of bursts of frontal delta and a handful of asymmetric bursts on the left seen in the initial portion of the record.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings on an adult of this age are nonspecific and can be seen in the context of a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old female present for follow-up. Last seizure was 01/08/2010 x 2 with loc. Patient has history of intracerebellar CVA, headaches, eclampsia and renal insuff.
MEDICATIONS: lasix, Lisinopril, Tegretol, Tylenol, ADA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic simulation was completed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized. There are some portions of maximal wakefulness where the overall pattern is reasonably well organized with a 9.5 hertz alpha rhythm. Other sections include bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity. In the transition to drowsiness, there is prominent arrhythmic delta activity and the overall background is more disorganized than one would except in a young adult. There is some shifting slowing and a single left temporal sharp wave is observed in this sharply contoured background. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is drifting in and out of stage II sleep and there is no significant driving response.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background disorganization particularly in drowsiness.
2. FIRDA.
3. Posteriorly predominant arrhythmic delta activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Only a single sharp wave was observed in this record. In this individual who is hospitalized on the 8th for complications of eclampsia, this is an improving pattern, but ongoing vigilance may be necessary.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 80 year old right handed female in status post cardiac arrest on February 5, 2010. Past history of seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Zocor, Vancomycin, Acyclovir, Keppra, ASA, Aricept, Bactrim, Moxifloxacin, Insulin, Lovenox, Dexamethasone, Ceftriaxone, Levothyroxine, dopamine, Norepinephrine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient had a seizure just prior to the EEG.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This EEG demonstrates some low voltage, subtlety discontinuous background. Some attenuation of about 3 seconds are interspersed with periods of low voltage, mixed theta delta. As the recording continues, the EEG is more continuous. There is some shifting asymmetries with more attenuation on the left compared to the right.

Seizure: The patient is in the ICU at the bedside. She starts to have rhythmic mixed theta delta out of the left hemisphere, particularly the temporal region at 10:36:43. This gradually builds up, but at 10:36:55 she starts to have a burst of fast activity out of the right hemisphere. The bursts of fast activity builds up exquisitely, while the left hemisphere as a different frequency of activity with rhythmic delta. This is followed by more of a generalized pattern characteristic of more of a tonic clonic pattern, although behaviorally the patient is only observed to be having facial and head twitching. The activity starts to slow at 10:37:41. As it stops, it shuts off at 10:38 on the right, but continues on the left before terminating abruptly at 10:38:20. Postictally there is prominent background suppression as was noted in the early portions of the record.

HR: 162 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A markedly abnormal background starting out with burst suppression pattern and actually ending with a burst suppression pattern.
2. A very complex seizure, which likely began on the left, generated to the right, with different frequencies of activity from the different hemispheres and a differential termination of the procedure.
3. Following the seizure there are handful of sharp waves on the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe underlying encephalopathy, as well as very unusual mechanism for epilepsy. This seizure pattern is more typical of a chronic epilepsy than acute reactive seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 69 year old female with myelodysplasia admitted with fever, agitation. Seizures on the 9th.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lantus, Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is a fair amount of muscle artifact but the patient is relatively cooperative.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a somewhat slow and disorganized pattern with a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and occasional posteriorly predominant delta. On one occasion there seems to be a right frontocentral sharp wave, but unfortunately muscle artifact makes it difficult to determine if similar waveforms might have been seen on the left. Features of drowsiness include increase in the posterior delta.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Occasional occipitally predominant delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been previously described. In this individual with a relatively recent, right frontocentral seizure, there was little epileptiform activity identified today, however, the patient's muscle and movement artifact might obscure this.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 87 year old woman with low-grade fever, cough, delirium, dementia, and falling.
MEDICATIONS: Haldol, Metoprolol, Heparin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The overall EEG includes a low voltage pattern, which includes primarily slower delta frequency activity of 2 to 3 Hz, a small amount of theta, and a small amount of alpha frequency activity, particularly in the frontocentral region. There is no well-defined alpha rhythm. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing with some hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing followed by vertex waves. There is also some more sharply contoured high amplitude slowing in this bedside recording in the parietal occipital regions, a little bit more prominent at P3.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing
2. Disorganization.
3. A relatively low voltage pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Some of the triangular shape waves noted in the background in sleep are probably POSTS, which are a normal variant. No epileptiform features are seen. The pattern described above is nonspecific and can be seen in the context of dementia or toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old male with grade II glioma, language difficulties,
evaluate for epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic simulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG demonstrates
a prominent intrahemispheric asymmetry with prominent arrhythmic delta activity in the
left hemisphere and a prominent breach rhythm. The alpha rhythm is approximately 8
Hz bilaterally. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. In this sharply
contoured record, there are a handful of suspicious sharp waves, particularly T1. Photic
stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR: 66bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.
2. Rare left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Compared to the previous studies,. this EEG is markedly
improved.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old right handed woman with syncope, extensive cerebrovascular disease, and seizure in late February.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is a great deal of EKG artifact throughout this EEG, but despite the EKG artifact, there is a right anterior temporal sharp wave with focal slowing in the right frontal central region. Occasional bifrontal shifting slowing is noted as the patient transitions to stage 1 sleep. Other features of sleep include an increase in beta activity followed by vertex waves.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right anterior temporal sharp waves
2. Right frontal focal slowing
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. If there are additional questions, given the large quantity of EKG artifact, a follow-up study may be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 44 year old woman with epilepsy, past history of traumatic brain injury status post fall, seizure, loss of consciousness and hepatic laceration.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Tegretol, Motrin, Morphine, Reglan,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is a bedside study in an awake patient. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there are portions where the background EEG is well-organized with a 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm but this is disrupted by rhythmic, high amplitude frontal delta. Shifting asymmetries are observed in the frontal regions. The rhythmic frontal slowing is variable at some points, a little more arrhythmic on the right or the left and there are 1 or 2 suspicious left frontotemporal sharp waves observed. Features of drowsiness include an increase in the frontal rhythmic delta activity. In addition, is rhythmic background slowing.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:1. Rhythmic background slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 17 year old woman with ticks, staring spells, attention deficit disorder, recent gastroenteritis, drop attacks, and a tonic clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Bactrim and inhaler.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is abnormal. The background is primarily rhythmic theta with smaller amounts of delta. The definable posterior dominant rhythm is 5 Hz in a background with theta and delta. There are bursts of frontally predominantly spike and wave complexes noted in relaxed wakefulness. These are slightly asynchronous. Most are 3-5 Hz and in relaxed
wakefulness the bursts of generalized spike and wave activity are 1-3 seconds in duration. There are also some independent, isolated right or left temporal sharp waves noted in the background.
Hyperventilation is performed and produces an increase in the activity. In addition, during hyperventilation the patient complains of rapid or prominent heart rate.
Her baseline heart rate exceeds 100 beats per minute and in fact averages 110, actually dropping briefly to 96 during hyperventilation and then returning to tachycardia. Brief drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic slowing with spontaneous arousals. Lambda is observed in wakefulness.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response with supraharmonic driving at 11 Hz. In addition, there is a suggestion of a photo paroxysmal response as well. This is more clearly defined with frontally predominant polyspike activity with 19 Hz photic stimulation.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant spike and wave activity.
2. Background slowing and disorganization.
3. A suggestion of focal epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient's frequent seizures may contribute to the background disorganization. The epileptiform activity may represent a primary generalized or secondary generalized focus. Additional recording may be helpful following initiation of treatment.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old male with skull fracture, complex partial epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Codeine, Phenytoin, Metro, CEFEPIME, Vane
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is awake and talking.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates relatively rhythmic background slowing with a 7 hertz theta frequency pattern. The activity is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right. Asymmetric eye artifacts are noted and the skull defect is most prominent in the right frontocentral region. In addition, there appear to be a handful of right frontal/F4 sharp waves.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Amplitude asymmetry.
3. Right frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded. This EEG demonstrates a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function affecting both hemispheres. The sharp waves are in the right frontal region, in the region of the previous brain surgery.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 52 year old right handed woman with status epilepticus on April 2, 2010.
Hx of alcoholic dementia and CHI.

MEDICATIONS: Trileptal.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no hyperventilation nor photic simulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG in wakefulness is disorganized. There is a posterior dominant rhythm of 9Hz in the background with excess theta. There is an asymmetry in the alpha rhythm and at times it is more prominent on the left with more beta  activity on the right. Shifting slowing is observed but the slowing is more prominent on the right compared to the left and there is a right frontal sharp and slow wave complex noted. As the patient becomes drowsy, the right frontal epileptiform activity is more well defined with a spike and slow wave morphology, then spread to the frontotemporal region and phase reversal at F8 or FP2. In addition, in the later portions of the record where epileptiform activity is more prominent, the focal slowing in the right hemisphere is also more prominent with more disruption of faster frequency activity.

HR: 70 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right frontal sharp waves.
2. Generalized background slowing.
3. Focal slowing in the right hemisphere.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. These findings may be correlated with the MRI. No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old right handed woman with syncope, extensive cerebrovascular disease, and seizure in late February.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is a great deal of EKG artifact throughout this EEG, but despite the EKG artifact, there is a right anterior temporal sharp wave with focal slowing in the right frontal central region. Occasional bifrontal shifting slowing is noted as the patient transitions to stage 1 sleep. Other features of sleep include an increase in beta activity followed by vertex waves.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right anterior temporal sharp waves
2. Right frontal focal slowing
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. If there are additional questions, given the large quantity of EKG artifact, a follow-up study may be useful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old right handed female with bipolar disease and chronic headaches.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Lamictal, Valium, Morphine, Diovan
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy or in stage II sleep throughout much of the record. The background is remarkable for abundant 13 and 15 Hz beta frequency activity as well as frontal artifact. The patient awakens for photic stimulation and for hyperventilation and at that point an 11 Hz alpha rhythm is identified but rapidly drifts back into a sleep state.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The excess beta described above may be due to the use of sedative hypnotic medications. In addition, the fact that the patient is quite sleepy may be part of either her sleep deprivation or her pharmacologic sedation. No epileptiform features were identified in this EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old male with end-stage renal disease, multiple severe medical
problems, intubated in the ICU, found with a blood glucose or 900. Obtundation but no clinical
seizures. Bilateral CVA's
Protonix, Ativan, Insulin, Zosyn
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10รก
20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient1s quite obtunded but has
some cranial nerve findings.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begin s, the background EEG is markedly
suppressed. There is a lower voltage subtle, periodic delta with a-sharp wave mixed in. This
sharp wave is picked up at T2, T4-C4, perhaps maximum at T4-C4. Stimulation of the patient
on 1 occasion produces a clear change in the background with rhythmic periodic activity. In
addition, there is some sustained periodic discharge in the right hemisphere, which seems to
have an admixed right central temporal sharp wave. Looking at the video, it appears that the
patient has movement of the right thoracic region In association with this. This discharge Is brief
and subsides on its own. A second, remarkable discharge Is identified with sharp activity
present bilaterally but clearly maximum in the right hemisphere. On this occasion, the video
does not identify a clinical correlate and this second event is without a doubt an electrographic
seizure. In total, there are 3 well-defined electrographic seizures noted in !he record. One of
!hem seems to be stimulus sensitive and other 2 did not have clear clinical correlates.
HR: 120-150 bpm
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Three electrographic seizures.
2. interictal pattern of marked background suppression.
3. Epileptiform activity, which Is primarily on the right but is complex in nature.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function. It
also demonstrates a very irritative focus on the right. Ongoing EEG monitoring was requested
to determine the patient's response to therapy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old woman with complex neurologic history, admitted with back pain, history of diabetes, peripheral neuropathy, past stroke chronic left hemiparesis. Acute RACA and cerebellum CVA
MEDICATIONS: Morphine, Oxycodone, Narcan, Insulin, Morphine, Amlodipine, Metoprolol, Lovenox
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is initially quite somnolent but by the end of the record has transitioned from a face mask to nasal cannula oxygen and is uncomfortable, intermittently shifting her arms and is quite tachypneic. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing beings, the background EEG is quite slow with a mixture of delta and theta. There is a bit more theta in the temporal regions. There is a suspicious underlying sharp wave in the occipital region maximal at O1. Stimulation of the patient does not seem to produce a clinical alerting response, but the EEG is remarkable for increasing faster frequency activity. At the end of the record, the patient is more interactive and is a bit more tachycardic.
HR: 104 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Significant background slowing.
2. Shifting slowing, at times a little slower on the left compared to the right.
3. Question of an underlying O1 small, discrete spike.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The findings described above are nonspecific. The diffuse disturbance of cerebral function can be due to medications, underlying cerebrovascular disease or postictal state. The occipital sharp wave may be correlated with imaging. No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 65 year old male with a episode of garbled speech yesterday
which was transient. Past history of epilepsy 3 years ago.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Protonix, Zofran
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
stimulation are performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 7 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. There is a small degree of excess theta and background disorganization.
Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and produces an asymmetric
response with more prominent rhythmic theta delta from the right frontotemporal region
compared to the left. Following this as the patient becomes drowsy this asymmetry
persists. Photic stimulation is performed shortly after the hyperventilation and the
asymmetry remains. Photic stimulation does not otherwise activate the record.
Additional features of drowsiness include an inc..ease in background slowing which is
relatively symmetric.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing from the left frontotemporal region, which is accentuated by
hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural functional process on the
left, as well as a mild, diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old gentleman status post slab injury and acute trauma on May 9th. Episode of cardiac arrest in the trauma bay with shaking. Evaluate for myoclonus.

MEDICATIONS: Versed, Dilantin, Ciprofloxacin, Flagyl

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is intubated and febrile as described above. Current body temperature 103.8.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG does demonstrate a preserved cerebral pattern. There is low to medium voltage, mixed frequency primary theta frequency activity of 5.4 hertz, but there is also some 3.5 hertz delta activity and smaller amounts of beta. In this video study, the patient is postured with his head looking to the right. The big EEG machine and video camera are on the left. The camera demonstrates intermittent jerking of the chest and this correlates with some muscle artifact seen diffusely through the EEG. The brief jerks of muscle artifact are not clearly associated with epileptiform activity. There is a suggestion of a vertex sharp wave seen independently of the jerks and on 1 or 2 occasions, as the recording continues, there does appear to be a slow wave that follows some of the jerks. There is a small degree of discontinuity.

HR: 144 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. A primarily theta/theta delta pattern following cardiac arrest.
2. High amplitude myoclonic jerks, but some of these seem to have an after going slow wave.
3. Vertex sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The presence of an after going slow wave would suggest that the myoclonus is epileptiform in nature. Additional intervention may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 17 year old right handed female with onset of absence epilepsy
February 2010 with absence and tonic-clonic seizures, now seizure-free since February.
The patient is no longer having fevers, sweats or tics.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20

Approximately 10 seconds Into the arousal state with the bilateral alpha as the patient becomes agitated,
more rhythmic4-5 hertz activity emerges from the left central and parietal regions. The behavior of of the
patient is difficult to observe because the caregiver is trying to restrain the patient. The patient is
described as agitated and poor1y responsive by the caregiver during the seizure. He seems to have
looked to his right during the seizure although the caregiver approaches from the left obscuring the view.
A second seizure occurs and again Is characterized by first a somewhat slow background and then in this
case at 16:56:05, a burst of bilateral fast activity following the appearance of the theta on the left at
16:56:11 and then as this occurs, there is more fast activity bilaterally, more clear evidence of a breach
with higher amplitude fast activity more so on the left than the right and then more definitive frequency
evolution is noted at 16:57:11 as the patient postures through to the right with head turning to the right
and what seems like a decorticate or dystonic posturing of the right hand more so than the left. He also
has some irregular respirations and then some clonic activity. There is a problem with the EEG and the
EEG stops recording although the video continues through the end of the seizure. The technologist
attempts to fix the EEG problems while the patient seems to have had a 3rd seizure during the EEG. A
4th event is noted at 17:04:44 again with the patient turning to the left and this seems to merge onto a 5th
at0:07.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Complex partial status epilepticus characterized by recurrent seizures from the left hemisphere
although they do begin with some bilateral fast activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 31 year old woman with cerebral palsy, refractory epilepsy, seizure-free for the past 4 years until she had a tonic-Donnie seizure 1 month ago followed by multiple seizures. Past history of stroke and epilepsy.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1. channel of EKG. The patient is awake. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG Is markedly abnormal with
primarily a theta frequency background. There are bursts of generalized spike and wave and slow spike and wave activity. 'The bursts are typically 3 to 5 seconds in duration. There is also some more restricted frontally predominant spike and wave activity, a little more at the midline. Focal epileptiform activity is also observed including CZ, C3, and left anterior temporal. What appears to be generalized paroxysmal fast activity of approximately alpha frequency is noted. The patient drifts off to sleep with vertex waves and in sleep there seems to be ongoing slow spike and wave activity. In the transition to sleep, felt parietal sharp waves are noted. HR: 60 to 70 bpm

1, Abnormal background.
2, Slow spike and wave activity with variable maximum, sometimes a bit more prominent in the left parietal region.

These findings observed today were not associated with clinical changes but if there are additional questions, additional EEG recording may be obtained. Correlation with the patient's imaging and anti epileptic drug levels is suggested.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This Is an awake through stage 2 sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD The patient appears to be drowsy throughout much of the record. There are some sections in apparent wakefulness where there is a pattern with 7.3 Hz activity in the background and some faster 15Hz activity. There is at times a 10Hz alpha rhythm. As the patient transitions into stage 2 steep with vertex waves, K-complexes and spindles., frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity is Identified at 3 to 5 Hz.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess background 7.5 Hz activity and wakefulness.
2. Frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave activity, identified quite prominently In sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The excess 7.5 Hz activity was not previously described in other records and may be part of this patient's underlying neurologic process or due to underlying sleep deprivation. It does correlate with a faster frequency harmonic also noted in the background. The generalized, polyspike and spike and wave activity has been previously described. No absence seizures were recorded; however, the patient does seem to be quite drowsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old female with cerebral palsy, multiple seizures, recent PEG tube placement due to aspiration pneumonia. This is an outpatient EEG.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The overall background is poorly organized. There is rhythmic, 5.3 Hz activity noted in the posterior regions on the right. This activity is somewhat faster on the left at 5.8 Hz. The overall background is high amplitude, poorly organized. Paroxysmal bursts of generalized 6 Hz activity are seen intermittently in the background. As the patient becomes drowsy, these bursts are a bit more prominent. There are rare left frontocentral sharp waves.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
3. An asymmetry in alpha rhythm with a slower rhythm on the right.
4. Paroxysmal bursts of rhythmic 5 Hz to 6 Hz activity.
5. Rare left frontal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support an underlying encephalopathy. The types of abnormalities described above are seen in a chronic static encephalopathy. No seizures were recorded. If additional information is needed, a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep can be of value.

Superimposed upon this there are occasional high amplitude sharp waves picked up with a generous field of spread which are primarily in the left central regions but are picked up bilaterally. CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function, but the epileptiform activity came from the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 51 year old male with fungal cellulitis, septicemia.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Protonix, Folic Acid, Lantus, Bicitra, Protonix
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is not intubated, he sits with his head turned to the left and his right arm postured.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a overall slow pattern with a mixture of beta, theta and delta. There is a high amplitude periodic complex noted in the right hemisphere with some variability in terms of amplitude maximum. Sometimes it is maximum C4, other times right frontal. It may be high or low in amplitude. It does not demonstrate frequency evolution but it does have a very large field of spread. With the use of an average reference it is typically right frontal or central parietal. Occasionally after the sharp waves there is a brief attenuation in the background lasting approximately a second. The epileptiform activity can be reviewed at slow paper speed. In using slow paper speed there is no definitive evolution of the activity. Stimulation of the patient produces a withdrawal response but does not particularly activate the EEG.
HR: 112 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Continuous epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with subtle frequency evolution and some bursts.
2. Epileptiform activity right frontal or central and parietal regions.
3. Generalized background slowing.
4. Intermittent attenuation of the background.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG continues to demonstrate a highly epileptogenic pattern with subtle frequency evolution but without frank seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed male with primary generalized epilepsy.

MEDICATIONS: Topamax

IMPRESSION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are
performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG includes an 11.5 Hz
posterior dominant rhythm with posterior slow waves of youth. In relaxed wakefulness there are brief bursts of frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike in wave activity with bursts typically 1.8 seconds in duration. Most are under 2 seconds and none exceed 3 seconds in duration. Hyperventilation seems to accentuate these bursts. An attempt to test for responsiveness during stimulation is attempted but the bursts are so brief that it is not possible to complete the test before the burst is over. There are no deficits in recall identified during the bursts. On rare occasions as the patient becomes drowsy, some of the bursts are a bit more maximum in the right frontal region. Other features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. Photic stimulation elicits a small amount of bilateral driving, but the spike in wave activity is not accentuated by this.

HR: 66bpm.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant 3 to 5 Hz spike in wave activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are more compatible with primary generalized
epilepsy. The presence of a single isolated burst in the right frontal region does not exclude this diagnosis. This individual does not appear to have outgrown his epilepsy at this time.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed woman with epilepsy since age 12. The patient continues to have 3 nocturnal seizures per week. Complicated history of diabetes, hypertension, aortic valve repair, migraine headache and heart problems since birth requiring multiple surgeries.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an almost exclusively sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a stage I and stage II sleep with frequent transitions between stage I and stage II. There are vertex wave, K-complexes, spindles and POSTS. Asynchronous vertex waves with more prominent field of spread on the left in sleep.

The asynchronous sleep wave forms may be correlated with imaging. No definitive epileptiform findings were noted, however.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow.  There is excess theta identified.  There is a glimpse of an alpha reaching from 7-10 Hz.  In relaxed wakefulness, there are rare, high amplitude left anterior temporal sharp and slow wave complexes. Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta. After this, as the patient becomes drowsy there are subtle F7/T1 sharp waves noted. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.  Following photic stimulation a single, well defined right frontal temporal spike and slow wave complex is also noted and then later more discreet discharges, more compatible with a normal variant. In the final seconds of the EEG, another medium amplitude left anterior temporal discharge is identified, which is a spike. By the end of the recording, the background disorganization is somewhat improved.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes which are rare.
Excess background theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There is a single well defined sharp wave on the right which must be considered artifact, although may represent variable distribution of the left anterior temporal sharp wave.  The background slowing does improve a bit as the recording continuous, which may be part of a postictal phenomenon.  Correlation with imaging given the presence of focal sharp waves or spikes in an adult is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   49 year old male found with confusion.  With 2 seizures, hepatitis cirrhosis, markedly icteric.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Metoprolol, Prograf.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF BACKGROUND:  The background EEG is markedly low voltage and slow.  It is a mixture of low voltage beta at 15 Hz with smaller amounts of 2 to 2.5 Hz delta.  Stimulation of the patient produced a small amount of theta.  There is snore artifact.
HR:    108 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow background.
Prominent delta.
Prominent beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This electroencephalogram is compatible with a severe underlying encephalopathy.  Stimulation of the patient does produce reactivity.  A slow delta may be part of this patient's metabolic encephalopathy.  The beta reflects exposure to benzodiazepines.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  65 year old woman found down after acute onset of headache in the frontal half subarachnoid status post partial coiling of an ACOM aneurysm, postprocedure noted to have left face, arm, and leg twitching. Past medical history is significant for alcohol abuse, hypertension, and diabetes.
MEDICATIONS:  Nimodipine, Gentamicin, Dilantin, Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while comatose.  No activating procedures were performed, other than stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no clear posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  When the patient is stimulated during the recording, there is no clear change in the wave forms.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F4, continuously at a frequency of 0.5 to 1 Hz, representing periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLEDs).  It is apparent that with each of these discharges, although not always consistently, there seems to be clinical correlates in the middle of left shoulder twitching.
Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 70 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  Based on the description above, it is likely that the accompaniment of the PLEDs at F4 with the left shoulder twitching is consistent with focal motor seizures.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right frontal PLEDs and focal motor seizures.
Generalized slow waves with intermittent periods of attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals focal motor seizures arising from the right frontal region.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology but may be partly due to medication effect or cortical injury from the subarachnoid hemorrhage.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  65 year old with recent subarachnoid and right frontal external ventricular drain and just status post coiling with follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol, Keppra, Phenobarbital, Insulin, Gentamicin, Nimodipine, Lovenox, Protonix, Morphine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long term monitoring EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  No activation procedures were performed.  The patient was unresponsive during the recording.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture seen and no activation procedures were performed.  During the study, there is some noxious and tactile stimulation which caused no change in the frequency of the EEG.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at T3/T5 with additional sharp waves seen at C3/T3, both of them seen intermittently.
Focal slow waves seen at F4 intermittently. Please note that no longer F4 sharp waves are seen.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 2-70 mV.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left midtemporal and posterotemporal as well as central parietal sharp waves in addition to focal slowing in the right frontal region.
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability in the left hemisphere, specifically in the left posterotemporal and midtemporal region as well as the left parietal, central parietal regions.  There is also additional focal cerebral dysfunction in the right frontal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  Lastly, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology, but may be related at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.  Please note the differences in this report compared to the prior report where right frontal seizures were seen and this is no longer noted and has changed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  35 year old male with end-stage renal disease on dialysis and hypertension, with the last seizure in December 2011.

independent bilateral anterior temporal slow waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old right handed man with chief complaint of multiple seizures, lip smacking, turning the head the left, eyes rolled up, and became unresponsive with bladder incontinence.  He has a past medical history of hypertension and history of epilepsy.

Focal sharp waves seen at F8/A2 seen frequently throughout the recording, at times with a wide field.
Bursts of generalized slow waves with frontal predominance seen intermittently throughout the recording, also known as frontal intermittent rhythmic delta (FIRDA).

Right anterior temporal sharp waves.
(FIRDA) frontal intermittent rhythmic delta.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed male with new onset seizures, past history of alcoholism, subdural hematoma, craniectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.

The alpha rhythm is somewhat slow bilaterally, approximately 7-8 Hz.  There is excess theta.  There are some bursts of sharply contoured slowing and a handful of simple sharp waves in the left midtemporal region.  Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm and an increase in theta.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent amplitude asymmetry with higher amplitude activity on the right than the left.
A second asymmetry which includes a little bit more slowing and attenuation of activity on the left.
A handful of simple sharp waves.

POSTS are observed in stage I sleep. The patient is awakened for photic stimulation and demonstrates an alpha rhythm of 8 Hz.  Scant bilateral driving is noted.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess drowsiness.
A maximal wakefulness background slowing.
Bursts of paroxysmal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  The FIRDA and background slowing are nonspecific findings which could be due to a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function or a postictal state.  They may also be seen in a metabolic disturbance.  The irregular heart rate may be evaluated by other means.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  72 year old female with a history of diabetes, hypertension, and a stroke in 2006, presents with slurred speech and confusion which resolved in the emergency room.  She has bilateral PCA infarcts as well as small-vessel disease.

Focal slow waves seen continuously at F7/T3 and independently seen occasionally at F8/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
Generalized slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.

Continuous left anterior temporal slowing.
Intermittent right anterior temporal slowing.
Mild diffuse slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed male with post traumatic epilepsy after a major cranial and facial trauma at age 19.  Tonic clonic seizures increased in the last 6-8 months ago.  Sinus pathology with sinus tubes.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.   Hyperventilation was not performed due to the sinus problems, but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized, but there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is slight shifting asymmetries noted in the alpha rhythm and it is a little faster on the left than the right.  There is also a lit bit of slowing noted at some points when the alpha rhythm is identified and that slowing is on the right.  Arrhythmic delta is noted in the left hemisphere, particularly central temporal region.  There is a suggestion of a breech rhythm with both a beta accentuation noted at some points and some underlying sharp waves.  Unfortunately, artifacts are also noted in the same region.
Brief drowsiness includes vertex waves with transitions in and out of sleep.  Snore artifact is observed.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response better identified on the right than the left.  The patient continues to transition in and out stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles, again, some of which are asymmetric.
HR:    66  bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Shifting asymmetries and background disorganization.
Focal slowing in the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a process involving both hemispheres, the left perhaps more significantly than the right.  The sharply contoured slowing and sharp waves are on the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  55 year old right handed woman with 4 tonic-clonic seizures last month, admitted with confusion, the patient reported an aura just prior to this EEG.

This EEG demonstrates less in the way of right temporal sharp waves than previous studies.

Photic stimulation may have accentuated some of the epileptiform activity, but when the patient was stimulated, there is an arousal and a decrease in epileptiform activity.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Slow spike and wave activity.
Left frontal spike and wave activity.
Left occipital spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is not significantly different than the previous study.  No definitive clinical seizures were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old male, status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Midazolam, Valproic Acid
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous digital video EEG monitoring was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient has a pneumonia.  A pulmonary stimulator is utilized which produces artifact in the right scalp electrodes which resemble a seizures, but this activity is confirmed to be artifactual during the EEG.

The left hemisphere demonstrates focal slowing and sharp waves with left temporal sharp waves.  These are seen in wakefulness through stage II sleep.  No electrographic seizures are noted.
As the patient is increasingly awake and is extubated, the vest to mobilize the patient's chest secretions is used more substantially.  This produces artifact from the right temporal region, but the patient can be tested at the bedside.  The artifact will stop when the device is turned off and the patient is awake.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG monitoring session due to:
Prominent epileptiform activity from the left hemisphere, improving over the 24 hour recording.
Focal slowing with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left.
Somewhat slow record on the right.
Rare sharp waves on the right, including T6.
Interesting artifact produced by the pulmonary device, which resembled a seizure, but was confirmed not to be a seizure.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old female found down with a PEA code on the 28th of March, shocked a total of 3 times, then having a second PEA code for 22 minute and a third one for 50 minutes.  By the time she had arrived, she was cooled and now she is having myoclonic jerks.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed, Depakote, Midazolam, Heparin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Myoclonic jerks.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive and having jerks. No activating procedures were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely low attenuated background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontocentral beta.  Patient had no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Throughout the recording, there are frequent frontally predominant and right more than left sharp waves which appeared to start and decrease in frequency for about 2-10 seconds with some minimal spread to the left hemisphere.  During these discharges, the patient appears to move and it is difficult to be clear of the precise locations of the discharges.  In between these discharges, there is diffuse attenuation and cortical suppression in the EEG.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Frequent bilateral frontally predominant discharges with some right-sided asymmetry.
Evidence of diffuse cortical attenuation in between the bursts.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and attenuation in addition to frequent myoclonic seizures which appears to have a bilateral frontal onset and lateral right-sided predominance.  It is possible that the known left cortical stroke is causing this asymmetric appearance.
The presence of these discharges after a posthypoxic event carries a poor prognosis.  The lower attenuation is likely due to diffuse cortical dysfunction, however, there may be some influence due to the sedation medications.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and attenuation in addition to frequent myoclonic seizures which appears to have a bilateral frontal onset and lateral right-sided predominance.  It is possible that the known left cortical stroke is causing this asymmetric appearance.
The presence of these discharges after a posthypoxic event carries a poor prognosis.  The lower attenuation is likely due to diffuse cortical dysfunction, however, there may be some influence due to the sedation medications.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Post partum, 27 year old female, who delivered at 26 weeks gestation on April 4, 2012 with eclampsia, positive family history of nieces and nephews with epilepsy.  MRI demonstrates posterior abnormalities.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Labetalol, Heparin, Motrin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat slow.  The alpha reaches 7.5 Hz. Features of drowsiness includes rhythmic background slowing with vertex waves, POSTS, as well as a handful of spindles in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in background theta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Abnormalities in this EEG include slowing of the alpha rhythm.  In addition, there are a handful of sharp waves, typically at T1, but with some at T3 noted in relaxed wakefulness and accentuated in hyperventilation.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The slow alpha rhythm is a nonspecific finding, it can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function, as well as in a disorder of a process
involving the thalamic and occipital pathways.  The left temporal sharp waves raise a concern for a focal mechanism for seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 19 year old right handed male with a past medical history of seizures since age 16, now presents with 2 to 4 a month with loss of consciousness and tonic-clonic shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed including photic stimulation and hyperventilation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some CZ electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were performed.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges; however, some abnormal discharges are seen during hyperventilation; see below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  During the recording, there are various bursts of generalized slowing at 2 to 4 Hz; however, intermixed with this slowing there are discrete bursts of well-formed generalized spikes and waves at a frequency of 4.5 to 5 Hz with a very high amplitude of about 80 to 100 microvolts.  These bursts last a maximum of 3 to 4 seconds and the patient appears to be able to count during them.  There does not appear to be any clear asymmetry, either.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of generalized spike and wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   53 year old right handed man with history of hemispherectomy in 1977 and CP, as well as encephalitis, renal cell cancer, diabetes, hyperthyroid, venous insufficiency, schizoaffective disorder, depression, and suicide attempt with a history of seizures.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to an asymmetric posterior dominant rhythm that is best seen over the left hemisphere with a frequency that at best reaches 9 Hz and appears to be reactive to eye opening.  Over the right hemisphere sometimes there is an attenuated posterior dominant rhythm, but it cannot be clearly seen, and overall the frequency over the whole right hemisphere are attenuated and cannot be clearly seen. The patient appears to go into drowsiness.  During the recording, photic stimulation is performed and there is no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized spike and wave with a high amplitude discharge seen maximally over the left hemisphere at F7/FP1 at a frequency of 2-2.5 Hz and an amplitude of about 35-100 mV.
The bursts last as long as 10 seconds with no clear clinical correlate.
Marked attenuation over the right hemisphere with lack of normal frequencies.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of generalized spike and waves with a left frontal predominance.
Marked attenuation of the right hemisphere.
Lack of normal frequencies.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy.  The marked asymmetry over the right hemisphere is consistent with the known right hemispherectomy.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   79 year old woman that presents with history of schizophrenia, diabetes, hearing loss, hypertension, GERD, anemia, with change in mental status.  She did not seem normal about 2 days ago, now nonverbal.
MEDICATIONS:  Morphine
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  During the recording the patient stimulated and there is some reactivity to the record with some muscle artifact and improvement in the frequencies.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV seen continuously throughout the recording at times with wave forms that have a triphasic appearance.
SEIZURES:  None.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed male with subdural hematoma, previously evaluated for refractory seizures, and readmitted with subdural hematoma and change in mental status.  Nursing home resident.  The patient was sedated with midazolam prior to transfer from an outside hospital.  He is now intubated and poorly responsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Dilantin, Midazolam.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The technologist notes a craniotomy defect on the right.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a periodic complex in the left hemisphere.  It starts in the left frontotemporal region but demonstrates significant spread throughout the left hemisphere and using different montages seems to end in the occipital region, phase reversing at O1 and O2.  The discharge has complex morphology and a periodicity of about 1 per second.  It can be considered PLEDS plus in that there is a little bit of variability and a little bit of theta frequency that goes along with it.  Stimulation of the patient seems to dramatically accentuate faster frequency activity from the right hemisphere, but not the left.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A complex epileptiform discharge from the left hemisphere which is periodic in nature and has a broad field of spread.
Markedly slow background on the left.
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a highly epileptiform and complex process on the left which spreads to the right.  Positive prognostic features include the remarkable variability and reactivity on the right.  This patient has epileptiform activity from either hemisphere.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old right handed male with left subdural hematoma, status post bur hole last week.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Dilantin, Zosyn, Flagyl, Protonix, Metoprolol, Lovenox
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrodes placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive, but unfortunately has a great deal of muscle artifact.  This EEG is markedly abnormal.  It demonstrates a slow more featureless pattern on the left.  There is complex epileptiform activity with discharge, which appears in the occipital regions involving 01, 02, but with significant spread in the right posterior quadrants.  Epileptiform activity is prominent in the occipital regions.  It is not all entirely identical, sometimes demonstrates a phase reversal and a referential montage.  It is often picked up with a maximum at P3 and then a lower voltage potential that follows in the occipital parietal region on the left and then spreads to the right posterior region.  Other sharp waves demonstrate a more significant involvement in the right frontal regions.  The activity on the left is quite attenuated.   Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity on the right.  Unfortunately stimulation of the patient also produces a great deal of muscle and movement artifact.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly attenuated activity in the left hemisphere.
Complex epileptiform activity, much of which is in the posterior quadrants, sometimes at P3, but sometimes in the left frontal region or in the right occipital region.
Moderate slowing from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings should be correlated with this patient's imaging as a fluid conduction can attenuated EEG activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old male who presented with right-sided weakness, left MCA infarct, COPD, HIV, hypertension, gout.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Corgard.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates a markedly abnormal pattern.  The initial sections of the record demonstrate an asymmetric pattern with marked suppression of activity on the left.  The right initially demonstrates low-to-medium voltage rhythmic delta.  As the record continues, there is some theta on the right.  There are also some portions with generalized attenuation of the background.  Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity is noted, right greater than left, as is eye blink artifact.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Marked attenuation or suppression of activity on the left compatible with a left middle cerebral artery infarct.
Markedly slow pattern on the right with rhythmic delta.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric process, but the process on the left suggests marked disruption of cerebral activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old male admitted on May 11 with alcohol withdrawal seizures versus epilepsy.  Evaluate for viral encephalitis.  CT scan showed diffuse cerebral edema.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vancomycin, Acyclovir.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and unresponsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a diffusely slow pattern.  It is a mixed frequency pattern with generous beta and theta.  There is intermittent attenuation of the background lasting about 1-2 seconds.  In addition, although there is some technical issues, the frontal regions sometimes demonstrate a bit more attenuation.  EEG is overall relatively symmetric. Stimulation of the patient produces an attenuation of the background.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a mixed frequency markedly slow pattern.
Intermittent attenuation of the background.
Flattening of the activity.  Flattening of the EEG in response to stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are nonspecific.  This EEG could be seen in a diffuse, serious disturbance of many different causes.  There were no specific hallmarks of a herpes encephalitis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old man with alcohol abuse, presented with seizures, found to have herpes encephalitis, now unresponsive and not following commands.  Follow up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Acyclovir, Vancomycin, Zosyn.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Follow up EEG for seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and while unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7 Hz seen mainly over the right hemisphere.  There is some frontal central beta seen best over the right hemisphere also.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient when stimulated appears to have some muscle response to stimulation.  Some patterns of sleep architecture, stage I, are seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slowing seen over the left hemisphere, maximally in the mid temporal and anterior temporal regions at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 mV.  In addition, in this region there is almost complete loss of the faster frequency, especially over the temporal and some over the left central region and the frequencies are all low voltage and attenuated.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left mid anterior temporal slowing.
Attenuation of faster frequencies in the left hemisphere
Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral structural dysfunction in the left anterior temporal and mid temporal region which, in addition with the loss of the faster frequencies is consistent with a known herpes encephalitis and damage to white and gray matter in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The reactivity can still be seen with some stimulation in the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old man with intermittent left upper and left lower extremity shaking since yesterday.  While getting hooked up today he had an episode of left arm shaking and head turning to the left.  He also has a history of alcohol use and possible withdrawal.  CT had hypodensity in the right large frontal parietal region.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Keppra,Thiamine
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow disorganized background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  The patient has no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen with a white field, but maximal at T4 with a frequency of 1-3 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV almost continuously throughout the recording with no clear evolution and some intermittent periods of pause for 2 seconds.  These are consistent with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges (PLED'S).
Focal slow waves at P4 in the right hemisphere maximal at P4 with a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Generalized slowing at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-40 mV.  Note:  The low amplitude seen diffusely and intermixed with this generalized slowing there is some bursts of 14-15 Hz discharges with a spindle appearance seen diffusely.
SEIZURES:  None seen.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemispheric maximal parietal PLED'S and slow waves.
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of right hemispheric maximal parietal focal structural dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with a known lesion seen on the CT.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  However, the spindle like discharges suggest it may be, at least in part, due to medication effect.  No seizures were seen during this routine recording.  If there is further concern for intermittent seizures, I would recommend continuous monitoring to evaluate for this occurrence.

Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 at a frequency at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Mild generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.

Left arterial temporal slowing.
Mild generalized slowing.
