CLINICAL HISTORY: 35 year old man with hypertension, pericarditis, alcohol abuse, HIV, lupus who presents with seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ativan, Protonix, Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness only.  Activating procedures are not performed except minor photic stimulation was performed for a couple of seconds.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded mainly during wakefulness.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EPISODES:  During the recording, the patient had 2 episodes where at the beginning he would start stretching his arm and becoming tense then his body started trembling slowly in his hands and his feet and developing whole body trembling lasting for about 1 minute 15 seconds, not being able to follow commands during the episode and not recalling the code word.  Afterward, he woke up and asked what happened and he was crying.  During this first episode, there was no clear EEG abnormality or changes and after the event there was a clear posterior dominant rhythm that could be changed.  During the event, there were just multiple artifacts.  A second event occurred minutes later while photic stimulation was started.  He started trembling slowly and the whole body started shaking irregularly and moving toward the left side.  This episode lasted about 2 minutes and again afterward the patient remained unresponsive for some time.  During the entire episode, the EEG did not reveal any epileptiform activity or any EEG correlate.  There was a lot of muscle artifact and after the event there was a clear normal posterior dominant rhythm seen during the recording.  Two episodes of diffuse body shaking with no unresponsiveness and no EEG correlate.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The 2 episodes with diffuse body shaking had no EEG correlate which is consistent with the diagnosis of a nonepileptic event.  No seizures or epileptiform activity were seen during the recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old woman found down, cardiac arrest for 20 minutes.

There is no normal sleep architecture.  No normal electrocerebral activity is seen.  There is only EKG artifact noted.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Absence of normal electrocerebral activity.

Absence of normal electrocerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of electrocerebral silence which in the right scenario is consistent with an EEG with presentation of breath death.
However, there are multiple artifacts due to the EKG and ICU which make it difficult to make a definite conclusion about this electrocerebral silence.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  73 year old male with acute right posterior MCA infarct with hemorrhagia conversion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow and low voltage.  It is somewhat lower voltage and slower on the right in comparison to the left.  There is a bit of head rocking artifact, but also some slower delta picked up in the right occipital and posterotemporal region.  Stimulation of the patient produces an alpha rhythm briefly which is not sustained.  The patient transitions into stage 2 sleep with scant, low voltage spindle.  An abnormal EKG with significant EKG artifact throughout the EEG.
HR:    90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Significant background slowing.
An asymmetry with a lower voltage pattern on the right in comparison to the left.  In addition, although there is more EKG artifact on the right, there is a bit of more slowing in the right posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function affecting gray and white matter.  No seizures were recorded and there were no epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  45 year old male status post two PEA codes on July 4, now with intermittent facial myoclonus, v-fib arrest on the 4th.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Zosyn, Vancomycin, Fentanyl, Dopamine, Lidocaine, Levophed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a discontinuous pattern.  There are intermittent bursts of fast activity followed by background attenuation.  The bursts of fast activity do not evolve.  Occasional facial twitching or muscle artifact is noted, but it does not impact the background.
The EEG until 2:47 was reviewed, and additional EEG recording will be performed to assess the response of therapy.
HR:    114 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
A post-anoxic pattern with discontinuity and bursts of fast activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This EEG carries a worrisome prognosis following anoxic insult and may be difficult to ameliorate.
EXTENDED EEG RECORDING SAME DAY
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Additional EEG recording is performed as the patient received IV Depakote.  Following the infusion of the IV Depakote, the patient continues to have a diffusely slowly and somewhat discontinuous pattern with brief bursts of fast activity.
Occasional muscle twitch is noted, but it seen sporadically, not in association with the bursts of fast activity.
HR:  N/A.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG was remarkable for:
A post anoxic pattern which was somewhat discontinuous with bursts of fast activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform seizures were seen.  These findings are worrisome following anoxic insult.

Excess theta.
Excess beta.
Somewhat poorly organized pattern for age.
FIRDA.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   44 year old man with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, phenobarbital, and Topamax.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike detection software as well as seizure detection software and nurses' alarm noted events were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves at F7/T3 seen occasionally in wakefulness and sleep.
Focal slow waves seen at F7/T3 at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  Seizure #1, 07/18/2012 at 10:30 a.m., complex partial seizure.  In the video, the patient suddenly places down his cell phone.  Suddenly his arms raise and he lays back.  After this, the right arm suddenly becomes dystonic and stiff.  He starts having automatic movements with the left arm, playing around with the cell phone and the sheet, and his face remains in a staring fashion.  At times he moves his mouth.  He continues this behavior during the entirety of the seizure.
EEG:  The EEG seizure started at 10:33 a.m. and ended at 10:34 a.m. The EEG correlate to the seizure started at 7 seconds after the clinical onset.  There is rhythmic theta discharge seen maximally at the beginning at T1/F7, which evolves in frequency and increases in amplitude.  It remains mainly over the T1/F7 electrodes but it spread throughout the whole left hemisphere.  After the end of the seizure, there appears to be an asymmetry of the faster frequencies with a lack of them over the left hemisphere.  End of seizure #1.
Seizure #2, complex partial seizure, occurred on 07/19/2012, starting at 2:48:57, ending at 2:49:52.  Video behavior:  While in bed the patient starts blinking and moving his mouth.  Suddenly his right arm becomes dystonic and his right eye shuts down and appears to twitch slightly while he continues to move his mouth.  Seconds later, he starts having rhythmic automatisms of the left hand and playing with the sheet.  He continues this behavior until the end of the seizure.
EEG:  About 10 seconds after clinical onset, the EEG reveals well-formed rhythmic 7 Hz theta discharge, maximal over the T1/F7 electrode, which is slightly obscured by muscle artifact which appears to continue to evolve in frequency and increase in amplitude over the left hemisphere.  The seizure remains on the left hemisphere.  It does not cross to the right.  After the end of the seizure, there appear to be a lot of faster frequencies over that left hemisphere and not noticed over the right.  The seizure lasts for 55 seconds.  End of seizure #2.
Seizure #3, electrographic seizures.  During the record, he had about 4 distinct electrographic seizures which were comprised of rhythmic runs of F7/T3 theta discharge that appeared to increase slightly in amplitude and then suddenly stop.  These 4 events lasted as long as 4 minutes.  During them, in the video there is no clear clinical correlate.  End of seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Left anterior temporal sharp waves and slowing.
2.  Complex partial seizures and multiple electrographic seizures.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This long-term EEG is diagnostic of localization related epilepsy with seizures arising from the left anterior temporal region.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old man with a history of seizures, hypertension, and bifrontal temporal gliosis who presents with seizures and frontal encephalomalacia.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Pantoprazole, Lovenox.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7/T3 and independently at T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 40 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal slow waves.
Right midtemporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontotemporal region with additional dysfunction in the right midtemporal region, both of which are consistent with the history of trauma and gliosis.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 48 year old female with a history of sarcoidosis status post lung transplant, now with head movements, hypertension, osteoarthritis, vulvar cancer, and here for electrocerebral silence evaluation.
MEDICATIONS:  None mentioned.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Brain death.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the brain death protocol using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while comatose and unresponsive.  To review the EEG, electrocerebral silence montage and double-distant electrode protocol was used.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  EKG artifact seen throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a completely suppressed background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no activating procedures were performed.  During the recording, all the electrodes are tested.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  There is no normal electrocerebral activity seen throughout the entire recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Lack of normal electrocerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is markedly abnormal with the absence of normal electrocerebral activity.  In the appropriate clinical scenario, and in the absence of any sedations, is suggestive of brain death.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old right handed woman with a history of a stroke about 3 weeks ago who presents with right upper extremity weakness, pre-op for left carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Tylenol, Iron, Neurontin, Baclofen, Lovenox, Metoprolol, Lipitor, ASA
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left CEA.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7 Hz.  The patient has some lack of frontal central beta.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen at F7/T3 frequently and at times at F8/T4.
Generalized slowing of 5-7 Hz seen in wakefulness.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left more than right anterior temporal slowing.
Mild generalized theta slowing in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction in addition to left more than right anterior temporal focal cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  23 year old man with history of seizures since age 7, here for evaluation of seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Depakote.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a nicely formed posterior dominant rhythm at 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and stage I sleep.  Activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and asleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

RECORDING LENGTH:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 80-year-old woman with past medical history of dementia, TIA, left frontal infarct.  She is admitted now from a nursing home for change in mental status.  The patient had a staring episode lasting a few minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, donepezil, atorvastatin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm reaches 9 Hz activity. There is an anterior-to-posterior gradient but it is weak.  Additional diffuse polymorphic theta activity is present. Nearly continuous bifrontal polymorphic delta activity is captured as well.  Frontally predominant generalized delta activity (FIRDA) is observed occasionally.  Sleep is very fragmented with some sleep spindles captured.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.
FINDINGS:
Mild diffuse slowing.
Bifrontal slowing.
FIRDA.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 23-minute awake and asleep EEG due to mild diffuse slowing, moderate bifrontal slowing, and occasional frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).  Diffuse slowing is a nonspecific indicator of diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal bifrontal slowing may be indicative of bifrontal structural abnormalities. FIRDA (frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity) is a nonspecific finding and could be seen in encephalopathy, increased intracranial pressure, and deep white
matter abnormalities.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  83 year old with left carotid stenosis, intracranial stenosis, recurrent hemiparesis.
MEDICATIONS:  Colace, Senokot.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates stage I sleep with occasional vertex waves and POSTS. Stimulation of the patient produces theta.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG in a hypersomnolent patient due to:
Excess theta.
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Shifting slowing left more than right
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.  The sleep recording is relatively symmetric, but in the limited wakefulness there may be more of a disruption of faster frequency activity on the left.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old man with a history hypertension, sleep apnea, bipolar disorder, and schizophrenia who presents confused and not waking up; question for meningitis.
MEDICATIONS:  None mentioned.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There is continuous movement artifact throughout the recording.  The patient does not hold still, making this a very limited poor recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record did not reveal a normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is a generalized slow background with no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slowing at 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.  Please note that no clear focality could be elucidated from this limited EEG.
SEIZURES:  None
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This limited EEG reveals evidence of generalized cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology and may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 59-year-old woman with a stroke, diabetes, nonambulatory status, small vessel ischemic disease Left MCA and CVA seizures in 2010.  Follow up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed on a stretcher for this nonverbal adult, using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  The patient was able to nod yes to questions.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates moderate background slowing with primarily a theta frequency pattern and at times generous beta.  As the patient transitions off to sleep, there are bursts of frontal delta which are a little higher amplitude on the left and there is a small amount of shifting delta.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.  Features of drowsiness including increase in background slowing.  Heart rate irregular at 84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:  Relatively marked background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this awake adult who can communicate, this degree of background slowing is more compatible with a chronic encephalopathy.  No epileptiform features were observed. In contrast to 2010 EEG, this is now a pattern of generalized, not focal slowing. No sharp waves were seen this time

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old male with idiopathic cardiomyopathy, multiple episodes of ventricular tachycardia, ventricular fibrillation, arrest, previously on a fentanyl drip and responsive, now not following purposeful commands.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl drip, Cardene, Lasix, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and was unresponsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow with a pattern of rhythmic theta and rhythmic delta.  There is a bit more prominent frontal 3 Hz medium amplitude delta activity.  There is a small amount of shifting asymmetry.
Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.
Heart rate:  126 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG is markedly abnormal due to:
Marked background slowing.
Lack of reactivity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There is a small degree of variability with some sections of the record demonstrating an increase in beta.  This EEG supports a severe encephalopathy.  Contributing factors can include toxic metabolic and/or anoxic factors.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG during wakefulness.
DIAGNOSIS:  Change in mental status, rule out seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 42-year-old ambidextrous male with a history of catatonia, schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and obstructive sleep apnea who presents with increased agitation.  The patient is nonverbal since 09/15/2012.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Tegretol, baclofen, lorazepam, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed at the bedside using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This tracing captured the patient in a confused and agitated state.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is diffuse slowing of background activity consisting of 5 to 6 Hz theta activity intermixed intermittently with 1.5 to 2 Hz delta activity during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There were occasional bursts of frontal intermittent delta activity, FIRDA, seen with a frequency of 1 to 1.2 Hz and an amplitude of 60 to 70 microvolts, lasting for 1 to 2 seconds.  There is also a small amount of low amplitude diffuse beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple frequencies and did not result in a driving response.  The patient was agitated during the study, which makes the study limited due to the presence of movement and muscle artifact at times.  Heart rate 100 to 110 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of background activity with theta and delta range during wakefulness.  There is also FIRDA bursts during wakefulness.  This study is limited due to the presence of movement and muscle artifacts.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to metabolic toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the fact of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The generalized beta activity could be due to medication effect including benzodiazepines or barbiturates, or could be due to anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  The presence of FIRDA is also associated with increased intracranial pressure or midline brain mass.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures are captured.  This does not rule out a diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 71-year-old woman with senile dementia and possible epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Lasix, Seroquel, Ativan, Percocet.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was unable to participate in hyperventilation. Photic stimulation was completed.  This was an awake and drowsy record in a somewhat anxious patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Some sections of the record are reasonably well organized with a 6.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  This is excess beta and excess theta.  There is a small degree of disorganization noted in the background.  Photic stimulation does elicit driving with harmonic, supraharmonic and subharmonic driving.
Heart rate 120 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent slowing of the background.
Excess beta.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This slow EEG pattern is supportive of an underlying encephalopathy such as dementia.  It is not specific in terms of any particular type of dementia, but Alzheimer's type dementia and B12 deficiency can both produce this pattern, as can multi infarct dementia.  This patient's medications may play a role in the background slowing.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  24 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 53-year-old woman with a past medical history of seizures secondary to motor vehicle accident in 1994.  The patient reports approximately 3 seizures a month with the last seizure being on 09/28/2012.  The seizures are described as lip smacking, loss of train of thought, and aphasic.  Postictal period is characterized by migraine and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Fioricet, meloxicam, Singulair, loratadine, and Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 9-10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is fast alpha variant.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies and lower amplitudes observed anteriorly.  Drowsiness is captured, but stage II sleep is not recorded.  Hyperventilation is performed and is characterized by symmetrical diffuse slowing as well as accentuation of left posterior quadrant sharp waves.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.  There are intermittent moderate amplitude sharp waves with slow waves observed over the left posterior quadrant with phase reversal over T5 and O1 electrodes.  Occasionally there is a reflection over the right posterior quadrant leads.  No electrographic seizures are captured.
FINDINGS:  Intermittent sharp waves over the left posterior quadrant, primarily observed over T5, O1 electrodes.  No electrographic seizures.  No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 24-minute EEG due to intermittent epileptiform discharges over the left posterior quadrant, most notable over T5 and O1 electrodes.  This finding indicates underlying structural dysfunction that carries an epileptogenic potential.  No electrographic seizures are captured.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old male with post traumatic epilepsy, frontal and bitemporal gliosis. Patient had multiple major motor seizures with elevated Tegretol level of 18, sedated with Ativan and Versed.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, lisinopril, carbamazepine, Ativan, Versed, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The patient is drowsy.  The background is diffusely slow with a mixture of delta and theta.  Stimulation of the patient produces eye movements and increase in delta.
The patient is initially not cooperating or not talking to the technologist.  As the recording continues, the patient is conversant despite a markedly slow background.
Heart rate:  104 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to: Significant generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEGs were not available for comparison.  This EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function and may occur with a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy or postictal state.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old male with HIV and 6 months of vertigo.  Vertigo occurs without head movement.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperdal and Celexa.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.
Hyperventilation produces slowing of the background.
There are sections of the record when the patient is maximally awake, such as during photic stimulation where the alpha rhythm is somewhat slow, 7.8 to 8.3 Hz.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
Heart rate:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to:  Intermittent slowing of the alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  The mild background slowing is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral dysfunction due to many different causes.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study may be of value.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 36-year-old man with history of seizures, presented in status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Vancomycin and phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and lethargy/stuporous.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Heart rate is 90.
The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There were no activating procedures.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at T5 and at times moved more forward to T3 and very rarely at T6.
Focal slowing seen at T5 frequently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-50 microvolts.
Generalized slowing at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
There were intermittent bursts of prolonged lasting frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA).
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterotemporal and midtemporal sharp waves with rare right posterotemporal sharp waves in addition to generalized slowing of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with seizures possibly arising from the left posterotemporal or even the right posterotemporal region. There is also evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left posterotemporal region , which is non-specific with regards to etiology.  Lastly there is evidence of  generalized cerebral dysfunction, of which is nonspecific with regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures for a month.  Last one 1 week ago consisting of generalized tonic/clonic shaking with tongue biting.  Sometimes he has blinking tremors and staring.  Also has hypertension and reflux.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Restoril, and Zantac.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakeful state and sleep.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation.  It did reveal some normal discharges which will be described next.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
Heart rate:  54.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Burst of generalized spike and wave at 3.5 to 4 Hz were seen frequently throughout the recording.  These bursts were anterior predominant and symmetric and lasting a maximum of 2 seconds.  There appeared to be no clinical changes during these episodes that the technician could note.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized spike and wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old with epilepsy since childhood.  The patient was a limited historian, but seizures include loss of consciousness and postictal confusion.  Previous seizures earlier this week.  Last seizure prior to October 25 was July 12.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is both excess beta and excess theta noted in the record.  Although there is some technical issues, including muscle artifact for a patient who has difficulty relaxing, there is excess theta and minor shifting asymmetries.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Drowsiness produces an increase in the rhythmicity of the background.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Mild excess theta.
Mild excess beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The excess beta and theta may be postictal findings.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 62-year-old male with liver disease, hypertension, and stroke and epilepsy admitted after found unresponsive with incontinence, possible witnessed shaking spell.  Now confused.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was confused.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It is diffusely slow with high amplitude, sharp waves and spikes from the left hemisphere particularly in the frontotemporal region.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle.  When the technologist stimulates the patient, the patient is inattentive but there is no increase in epileptiform activity.
This is a technically challenging EEG for an individual who his very active with tactile stimulation but as he drifts off to sleep, the epileptiform activity is well defined.
Heart rate 75 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly slow background.
Left anterior temporal spikes and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG suggests a highly epileptiform focus.  This is likely a postictal record but ongoing vigilance is essential.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was confused.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It is diffusely slow with high amplitude, sharp waves and spikes from the left hemisphere particularly in the frontotemporal region.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in muscle.  When the technologist stimulates the patient, the patient is inattentive but there is no increase in epileptiform activity.
This is a technically challenging EEG for an individual who his very active with tactile stimulation but as he drifts off to sleep, the epileptiform activity is well defined.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63-year-old female with a history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and right sensory neural hearing loss presents to us due to paresthesias on the left face and arm, found to have a right frontotemporal mass.
MEDICATIONS:  Ancef, labetalol, hydralazine, morphine, potassium, midazolam, gentamicin, dexamethasone.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some multiple electrode artifact seen throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage I and stage II sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Heart rate:  60 and regular.
Abnormal discharges:
Continuous focal slowing seen at C4/T4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 microvolts.  At times this is sharply contoured.
Intermittent focal slowing at times seen at F7/T3, frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to continuous right central temporal focal slowing as well as some intermittent left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the right central temporal region, which is consistent with the known mass.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Preop for aortic arch replacement.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old man with a past medical history of aortic valve replacement in 2012 with complications and with IV drug use, diabetes, depression, anxiety, hepatitis C, with complaints of leg and back pain, found to have an aortic and bilateral iliac thrombus and he is preop for aortic arch replacement.
MEDICATIONS:  Pepcid, morphine, Lopressor, paroxetine, methadone, heparin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy and stage 1 sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 5 Hz which appears somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is some faster frequencies in frontocentral beta seen intermittently and some stage 1 sleep architecture appears to be seen.  Overall, there is a diffusely slow background in the delta range seen almost continuously throughout the recording.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen over the right hemisphere, maximum at T4, at times at F8 seen frequently throughout the recording.
Generalized slow wave at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts is seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to right midtemporal focal slowing as well as generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right midtemporal region, with an additional diffuse cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The primary team was informed of these abnormal findings in the EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 54-year-old woman with epilepsy, admitted to the hospital on the 30th after a tonoclonic seizure with postictal confusion.  The patient remained mute after the seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote, Ativan, Keppra, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was initially somnolent, then inattentive.  This was an awake through stage II sleep record.  After the patient drifted off to sleep, it was somewhat difficult to awaken the patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The tracing begins with stage II sleep with central spindle activity.  Focal slowing is noted from the left temporal region with left temporal sharp waves.  The sharp waves are mid to anterior temporal with a generous field spread.  They are discrete, at 70 microvolts at the maximum.  In the T1 and T2 montage they are maximum at T1.
The patient is still quite drowsy during photic stimulation.  During photic stimulation, there are trains of left anterior temporal sharp waves as the patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep.
The technologist attempts to awaken the patient for hyperventilation without success.  The patient remains in stage II sleep again with prominent sharp waves from the left temporal region.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves.
Left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are relatively characteristic of temporal lobe epilepsy.  This patient's postictal state may account for the hypersomnolence as it might be the use of benzodiazepines.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 34-year-old right-handed female with past medical history of seizure disorders, childhood onset.  Her last seizure was 2 months ago, described as feeling dizzy and strange, lasting for 1-2 minutes.  Past medical history is also significant for neurofibromatosis.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the laboratory using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement, in addition to T1 and T2 electrodes and 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 11-12 Hz in frequency, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm, slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts.  There was intermittent burst of focal slowing in the left anterior and mid temporal regions at F7/T3 consisting of 2.5 to 3 Hz delta frequency activity, 30-40 microvolts in amplitude, lasting for 1-2 seconds. Hyperventilation results in slowing of the background most prominent on the left side.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate was 70 to 80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to intermittent bursts of focal slowing in the left temporal region during wakefulness and short periods of drowsiness.  There were no epileptiform abnormalities or seizures identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Left temporal slowing could be suggestive of an underlying structural abnormalities in the left hemisphere or left temporal dysfunction. There were no epileptiform abnormalities or seizures noted during this recording.  If seizures are of clinical concern, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 41-year-old male with recent onset of epilepsy, 3 nocturnal seizures with tongue biting.  Each seizure was associated with a low blood glucose.  The patient had violent swinging movements with one of the seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Insulin, Keppra, and enalapril.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness there is a small amount of shifting slowing with occasional, independent right or left temporal slowing.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing an increase in theta, a little bit more so on the left than the right.  Some of this was rhythmic, but some was somewhat arrhythmic as well.
Sleep was characterized by a prominent increase in beta.  Spindles were noted.  Again, there was a small amount of shifting slowing noted in sleep.  Vertex waves and POSTS were also seen.  As the patient transitions in and out of sleep, there was some rhythmic, hypnagogic hypersynchrony.
Photic stimulation was performed at the end of the record when the patient was awake.  A normal background was noted at that time.  Despite the tech's attempt to maintain him in an awake state during photic stimulation, the patient started to drift off to sleep during photic.  A driving response was elicited.
Heart rate:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to: Occasional bursts of shifting slowing noted as the patient transitions in and out of drowsiness and in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No sharp waves or spikes were seen.  There were no specific hallmarks of an underlying seizure disorder.  The shifting slowing noted in the transition to sleep is characteristic of that seen in older adults with cerebrovascular disease.  It is, however, a nonspecific finding.  In this individual with new onset seizures, perhaps a more prolonged sleep recording may be helpful in the search for epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old right handed gentleman with post traumatic epilepsy, 4 to 5 seizures a months, sometimes with an aura but frequently with injury.  Past long term EEG monitoring in 2005 with discreet right frontal/frontotemporal sharp waves but no seizures recorded so far with inpatient EEG monitoring or digit trace monitoring.  Recent seizure on the 26th with fall with loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  There are occasional bursts of shifting slowing but a little bit more prominent than the right posterior temporal region.  There is also some head rocking artifact in this region.
Hyperventilation seems to accentuate some focal slowing in the right and there is a questionable right frontotemporal sharp wave noted in hyperventilation.
There are rare, right frontal sharp waves at SP2 (2).
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
A small amount of shifting slowing.
Subtle right posterior temporal focal slowing.
Rate right frontal sharp waves.
The right mid temporal sharp waves were seen on only 1 occasion and therefore cannot be considered definitively pathological.  The findings described above are similar to previous studies.
This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.  Of note, the patient's epileptiform activity was more prominent in the past.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 66-year-old woman with history of epilepsy.  The patient repeatedly stops seizure medicine.  Ran out of Keppra and has had multiple spells.  Two to 4 seizures per month.
MEDICATIONS:  Imitrex, Fosamax, and many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Occasional bursts of shifting and flowing are noted from the right or left temporal regions.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in rhythmicity of the background followed by post and subtle vertex waves.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting in and out of sleep but a driving response was obtained.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing.
Disorganization.
Shifting and slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are similar to a previous study made 2011 but there is a little bit more background slowing and shifting slowing.  Correlation with clinical history and imaging is important for this older adult with multiple medical problems.

STUDY DATE:  11/30/2012.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Syncope.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 72-year-old female admitted with syncope and a sudden change in mental status after a code with tachycardia and  hypertension.
MEDICATIONS:  Tramadol, Tylenol, lorazepam, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while awake and drowsy.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at times reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta seen.  In general, the background has intermittent theta bursts even during wakefulness at 6-7 Hz seen diffusely.  The patient does appear to become drowsy at times.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Excessive theta in wakefulness at 5-7 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen intermittently throughout the recording.
Abnormal discharges:
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 63-year-old man with acute stroke and status post left hemicraniectomy and large epidural hematoma with a craniectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while obtunded.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  Overall the background consists of diffuse slowing with attenuation of frequencies over the entire left hemisphere and focal slowing seen maximal in the left frontal region.  Over the right hemisphere, there is mainly theta/delta frequency at 2-4 Hz, amplitude of 20-60 microvolts, and at times faster in theta.  There appears to be no reactivity to the EEG with stimulation.  At times over the right hemisphere, there are some sharply contoured waveforms at T6 and T4.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Left hemisphere attenuation and focal slowing maximal over the frontal region.
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz, amplitude of 20-40 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
HEART RATE: 108, rhythmic.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left hemispheric attenuation and focal slowing maximal in the frontal region as well as generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural cerebral dysfunction in the left hemisphere, maximal in the frontal region, involving both gray and white matter, which is consistent with the known stroke and hemorrhage.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or clear epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 57-year-old male with epilepsy, status post craniotomy.  The patient was admitted 2 days ago with a seizure and aspiration pneumonia with metabolic acidosis.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, ciprofloxacin, Ativan, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized.  There is an alpha rhythm which is typically 8 Hz, sometimes reaching 9 Hz with generous beta and theta.  A likely breach rhythm is noted in the left frontocentral region with accentuation of faster frequency activity in that region.  Additional, irregular mixed theta and delta seen in the left mid and posterior temporal regions intermittently.  Features of drowsiness including increasing beta as well as somewhat irregular delta in the left temporal region and rare left temporal sharp waves.  The focal slowing is more prominent as the patient becomes drowsy.  It is also a bit more continuous.  Spontaneous arousals from sleep were observed.
Heart rate 102 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Left temporal focal slowing.
Excess beta.
Occasional left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Previous EEG's were not available for comparison.  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy.  Comparison of previous EEG's may be valuable.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  An 80-year-old male with adult onset epilepsy and dementia, patient had multiple seizures this morning including 5 seizures and then a tonic-clonic seizure in the emergency room.  Seizures typically occur with dehydration but not exclusively so.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, Depakote, glyburide, lisinopril, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Patient was very confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow and low voltage.  With arousals, a low voltage theta pattern was identified.  As the patient drifts in and out of sleep, there is some bursts of some shifting slowing and some muscle artifact.
Heart rate irregular 117 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to replacement of normal background with a low voltage flow pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the third EEG without epileptiform activity for this adult.  The current pattern is compatible with a post ictal or pharmacologic pattern with a low voltage flow pattern.

.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 66-year-old female with abdominal pain, shortness of breath, and change in mental status, initially admitted to the medical ICU due to sepsis versus hypercapnia.  The CT abdomen found fluid collection and status post colectomy in 12/2009, had an episode of shaking, bilateral shoulders for 2 minutes, given Ativan and stopped.  She also has a past medical history of COPD, GERD, hypertension, SVT, and essential tremor.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Keppra, Flagyl, hydrocortisone, Advair, Protonix, cefepime, vancomycin, Lovenox, insulin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while slightly responsive while sedated.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some movement artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Overall, there is a diffusely slow background in the delta frequency at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-30 microvolts seen continuously.  At times, there is intermittent triphasic live waveforms which appear to be symmetric and maximally center frontally and at times periodic.
SEIZURES:  None.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-30 microvolts seen continuously.
Triphasic waves.
Heart rate 180, irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing as well as triphasics.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  However, the triphasics suggest at least a possible metabolic component.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 29-year-old male with endocarditis, status post code last night.  The patient had prolonged cardiac arrest, required temporary pacer and then developed myoclonic jerks today.  Now requiring dialysis.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, Versed, fosphenytoin, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated, comatose and had occasional jerks.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG pattern demonstrates a burst suppression pattern.  The overall pattern is suppressed with some ICU artifact.  At a sensitivity of 3 there is scant low voltage activity and ICU artifact. The bursts of activity are typically 1.5 seconds in duration and include muscle activity, some fast activity and a paroxysmal burst of slow at the beginning and one at the offset.
Stimulation of the patient did not activate the record.
Heart rate 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Burst suppression pattern with markedly suppressed activity.
Bursts which occur approximately every 10 seconds lasting 1-3 seconds in duration.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No clinical seizures were noted.  No spontaneous reactivity or variability were observed.  In this individual who is more than 12 hours post cardiac arrest, these findings carry a very worrisome prognosis.

EGG LENGTH:  Approximately 24 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 50-year-old man with a past medical history of a right MCA stroke, CHF, AICD, who now presents with a single episode of a fall followed by confusion and urinary incontinence.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, Keppra, Zocor, etc.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with slower waveforms at higher amplitudes over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of well-formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is also anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes observed over the left hemisphere.  There is no posterior dominant rhythm or anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the right hemisphere.  The background over the right hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity with under riding faster frequencies.  Diffuse excess beta is observed.  During sleep vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes are captured.  Sleep architecture is better formed over the left hemisphere.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.  Premature QRS complexes are captured on a single electrocardiogram lead.
FINDINGS:
Moderate continuous right hemispheric slowing.
Excess beta.
Stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal wake and asleep 24 minute EEG due to continuous moderate right hemispheric slowing.  This finding indicates focal right hemispheric dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and in this patient is consistent with a history of a prior right MCA stroke.  Excess beta could be secondary to a medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

STUDY DATE:  01/04/2013 to 01/05/2013, for a total of 7-1/2 hours.
REASON FOR STUDY:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 28-year-old man with a history of CAD status post percutaneous inflation in 2006, factor V deficiency, hypertension, DVT, and seizure disorder who presents with chest pain today with episodes of upper extremity generalized movements.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, lorazepam, __________, Protonix, Percocet, and Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  The patient did unhook his electrodes at 11:20:30 p.m.  It appears that he slowly took them one by one off; however, video was continued during the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 to 10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage I, stage II, and deeper stages of sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Heart rate 96.
Abnormal discharges:  Intermittent focal slowing seen at T3 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 20 to 50 microvolts.
Episode at 11:55 p.m.:  The patient was noted on video to suddenly stiffen his body, stretch out his right arm, grab up to the rail of the bed, and shake and tremble rapidly, causing the entire bed to shake.  The nurse came to talk to the patient and he appeared to be unresponsive.  The patient had his head stretched backward and it was not clear if his eyes were open or closed based on the video.  The episode lasted until 11:59 p.m.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to intermittent left midtemporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG revealed evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left midtemporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  The episode seen on video appears to clinically have features of a nonepileptic event; however, no clear commentary can be made since there was no EEG that could be reviewed during the time of the episode.  No further episodes were captured on this day #1 of monitoring.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 79-year-old man admitted for acute renal failure, change in mental status, with right-sided weakness and 2 tonic/clonic seizures with eyes rolling backwards and right facial twitching.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  T4 electrode artifact.
MEDICATIONS:  Amlodipine, loratadine, Dilantin, and vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely low slow background with normal posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture and no normal frontocentral beta seen.  No activating procedures were performed.  No sleep architecture was seen.
Heart rate:  114.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording with amplitude of 20-30 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to marked diffuse or generalized slowing.  This EEG reveals evidence of marked diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology but may be at least due in part due to medication affect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 39-year-old male who had a witnessed seizure, following backwards.  He was standing on the sidewalk.  He was intubated.
MEDICATIONS:  Percocet, Dilantin, midazolam, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was wearing a hard collar and had been extubated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This bedside EEG is remarkable for significant frontalis muscle artifact.  The patient transitions from wakefulness and sleep.  The overall EEG includes generous beta.  The patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  With arousal, there is some alpha and beta frequency activity, although the patient does not sustain wakefulness answers questions appropriately.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:  Excess beta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features noted.  The excess beta may be due to this patient's medications.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 73-year-old male with a seizure January 7th.  He was found to have generalized tonic-clonic shaking and postictal confusion.  Previous episodes with shaking and confusion.  Alzheimer disease, alcohol abuse, heart surgery, aggressive behavior.
MEDICATIONS:  Aricept and Haldol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  Hyperventilation was not.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  The overall EEG is relatively low voltage.  The patient transitions in and out of a drowsy state and as he does so, there are occasional bursts of shifting slowing followed by a pattern with rhythmic slowing.  Rare FIRDA is noted as the patient becomes drowsy.  Sleep was not sustained.
Photic stimulation elicited driving and supraharmonic driving.
Heart rate 42 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to a bit more shifting slowing in drowsiness than is otherwise accepted.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The mild shifting slowing is a nonspecific finding in an adult of this age and can be related to the patient's cognitive impairment or other age-related factors.  In this individual with multiple episodes which may be seizures, a repeat EEG or even more prolonged EEG recording may be of value.

BASELINE EEG
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 45-year-old woman with a strong family history of epilepsy, nocturnal tonic-clonic seizures, myoclonic jerks.  Vagal nerve stimulator.  There is a history of head trauma.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10-Hz alpha rhythm but there is a small amount of 7-Hz theta noted in the background.  Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record and produced an increase in theta.  As the patient transitioned in and out of stage 2 sleep, rare spike and slow-wave complexes were identified.  There was a burst of high-amplitude spike and polyspike activity in sleep which was generalized.  There was an additional subtle spike in sleep noted in the right frontal region.  Sleep was not sustained.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was transitioning in and out of sleep.  A photic driving response with harmonic and supraharmonic driving was observed but without spike and wave activity.  An additional burst of polyspike activity was noted as the patient was drifting off to sleep again at the end of photic stimulation.
Heart rate:  72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized spike and wave activity as the patient transitioned in and out of sleep.
Polyspike and slow-wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings have previously been seen in this individual.  Although not many abnormalities were identified, most of them were
generalized, not focal.  These may be correlated with clinical history and imaging, but this EEG is more supportive of a primary rather than secondary generalized epilepsy.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Syncope and a change in mental status.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with anterior temporal and single lead electrocardiogram electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, rifampin, simvastatin, evase (?), lisinopril, metformin, gabapentin, glipizide, ranitidine, carbamazepine, calcium.
HISTORY:  This is a 59-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy as well as childhood seizure and a previous craniotomy, left occipitoparietal craniotomy here with an EEG due to recurrent seizures.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some T3 and A2 electrode artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to diffusely slow background, however, in the limited wakefulness, she has a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  The patient does appear to go into stage I deeper stages and stage II deeper stages of sleep.  However, the architecture is slightly atypical.
Activating Procedures:  Specifically, hyperventilation accentuate the abnormal discharges which I will describe in the next paragraph.  However, photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal Discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen at T3, at times at T5 and sometimes at 01 occurring during sleep mainly, but sometimes during  wakefulness.
Focal sharp waves seen intermittently at T4.
Focal slow waves seen frequently at F7-T3, at T3, at T5 and at O1 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.   There is increased amplitude and increased frequency consistently with a breach rhythm over that region.
Focal slow waves seen at T4 intermittently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Please note that the focal slowing at times occurs in burst lasting up to 5-6 seconds that appear to be very high amplitude and with intermixed sharp waves specifically over the left hemisphere.
Heart Rate:  84, regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left posterior quadrant sharp waves and frequent focal slowing associated with breach rhythm as well as right mid temporal sharp waves and focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability in the left posterior quadrant, which is consistent with a known lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of right mid temporal focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  Overall, this EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of localization related epilepsy with multiple roci of irritability.  No clear seizures were seen during this recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 65-year-old male with history of recent onset dementia and forgetfulness.
MEDICATIONS:  Cyclobenzaprine, Xanax, tramadol, Aricept, Tylenol, Miralax, Namenda, tamsulosin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 6-7 Hz in frequency and 30-50 microvolt in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  The background activity is characterized by delta activity with a frequency of 1.8-2.5 Hz frontally predominant delta activity intermixed with 5-6 Hz theta activity.  There are intermittent bursts of frontal intermittent delta activity, (FIRDA) seen with a frequency of 1-1.2 Hz and amplitude of 50-70 microvolt lasting for 2-3 seconds. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation result in no responses. Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to the slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm and background activity and the presence of FIRDA bursts during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to metabolic encephalopathy, degenerative brain disease, increased intracranial pressure, or a deep midline lesion in the brain.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record. No seizures are captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This patient is a 32-year-old woman with cerebral palsy, accompanied by a caregiver.  The patient has had increasing seizures since January, hospitalized in area.  Eight seizures on the 19th, characterized by generalized tonic-clonic, staring.  These may occur out of sleep, in wakefulness has staring spells and premenstrual epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Dilantin, phenobarbital, p.r.n. Valium.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  Hyperventilation was not possible.  The patient was recorded in her specialized wheelchair.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It lacks the normal developmental milestones for an adult of this age.  The background includes an occipitally predominant spike, which can be maximal on the left or right.  There is a suggestion at times of almost an alpha rhythm on the right when the left is demonstrating slower spike and wave activity, although the alpha frequency on the right may be a harmonic of the activity on the left.  Fast activity accompanies the occipitally predominant spike and wave activity.  The overall background is somewhat chaotic, with mixed-frequency arrhythmic delta and more rhythmic 4-5 Hz theta noted.  Bursts of paroxysmal fast activity are noted in the frontocentral region.
Spontaneous arousals were noted in the background, with the appearance of muscle artifact.  With these spontaneous arousals the patient looks about and the epileptiform activity abates.  Then, in relaxed wakefulness there is higher-amplitude occipitally predominant paroxysmal theta, some of which is sharply contoured and some of which has a more clear either fast activity in the right occipital region or a spike in the left occipital posterior temporal region.  As the patient transitions into sleep there are vertex waves, but again central paroxysmal fast activity was noted.  The patient transitions in and out of sleep.  There are some frontally predominant triangular-shaped waveforms noted as the patient transitions in and out of sleep, but the vast majority of the sharp waves is occipitally predominant in this EEG.
Photic stimulation did not clearly activate the record, although there was abundant epileptiform activity noted during photic stimulation.
Heart rate was 90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to
Paucity of normal adult waveforms.
Occipitally predominant epileptiform activity, primarily on the left.
Paroxysmal rhythmic theta frequency activity of 5-6 Hz.
Rare triangular-shaped frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG differs from a previous study of October 13, 2010, in that there is more significant epileptiform activity in the occipital regions.  The paroxysmal fast activity was not noted, but the paroxysmal theta was previously identified.
These findings may be correlated with imaging and clinical history.  Given the abundance of epileptiform activity noted in both EEGs, the two studies may represent the depth of epileptiform pathology for this complex patient.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 29-year-old male with multiple intracranial abnormalities and daily seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, phenobarbital, Topamax, Trileptal, Clobazam, Klonopin, Dilantin.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The right hemisphere lacks the normal developmental milestones for an adult of this age.  The left hemisphere demonstrates high amplitude epileptiform activity with high amplitude versus slowing and a discrete spike in the left hemisphere, this is nearly isoelectric at T1.  Using an average reference, this appears in the left hemisphere, maximum a bit anterior temporally with a poly spike component and a generous field is spread throughout the left hemisphere.  The epileptiform activity is always maximum on the left but with volume conduction appears in the right frontocentral region as well.  High amplitude bursts were noted as the patient was drifting off to sleep without clear clinical correlate.  Some discharges are maximum in the left frontal region and those are more likely to spread to the right.  In some sections of the record, there is a lower voltage beta pattern with some left frontal central theta.  Bursts of epileptiform activity may be brief lasting more than 2 seconds or more prolonged and seemed to increase as the patient drifts off to sleep.  Features of sleep include an increase in beta frequency activity.  Vertex waves were noted.  At the close of the record, the patient seemed to be drifting off to sleep with more of a theta frequency pattern.
Heart rate 108 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent epileptiform activity primarily from the left hemisphere with a high amplitude on the left hemisphere slow spike, wave, and anterior temporal spike.
Left frontal spike.
Generalized background slowing.
A dynamic pattern with multiple different patterns including more of a theta pattern with focal slowing on the left.
Rare discrete sharp waves at T4
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  As was seen with previous EEG monitoring, the activity seems to be much more prominent from the left hemisphere.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 27-year-old female with history of cognitive dysfunction secondary to cerebral anoxia.
MEDICATIONS:  None.

There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness was characterized by diffuse background slowing, shifting of the posterior dominant rhythm to anterior head regions and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  There are intermittent bursts of left anterior to mid temporal slowing, 1.5-3 Hz frequency lasting for 1-2 seconds during drowsiness and wakefulness.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and resulted in no driving response.  Heart rate was 80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to the presence of intermittent left temporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or electrographic seizures were identified in this record.

No epileptiform abnormalities or electrographic seizures were seen in this record.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a repeat sleep deprived EEG or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.
