RECORD START TIME:  11:59 a.m.
RECORD FINISH TIME:  12:21 p.m.
RECORDING LENGTH:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old female with a history of epilepsy since age 11.  Her seizures occur more frequently now and are largely nocturnal.
MEDICATIONS:  Diazepam, divalproex and zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION:  __________
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the record opens, there is a well-formed and symmetric 9 to 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontocentral beta activity identified which is symmetrically distributed.  Stage 1 sleep is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the existing posterior dominant rhythm and the appearance of central theta activity.  Stage 2 sleep is not appreciated.
On at least 4 occasions during the record, there is the appearance of spike and wave discharges.  On at least 2 of these occasions, the discharges appear generalized with a bifrontal maximum.  These appear during periods of light drowsiness.  For approximately 3 to 4 seconds, there is a disruption of the background and the appearance of bihemispheric slowing superimposed upon which there is a sharply contoured activity.  There is, however, a definitive bifrontal generalized spike.  Later in the recording, there is a similar brief background slowing, and there is again bifrontal generalized spike and wave discharges.  These discharges are singleton events and thus it is difficult to determine what their frequency is.  On the third appearance, the spike wave discharges appears predominantly over the left frontal region and is maximal at FT7.  This discharge has the appearance more consistent with a localized focal spike in the left frontal region.
Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed in multiple flash frequencies and did not induce a significant photic driving response.  Of note, a photoparoxysmal response was not identified.  During the course of the recording, the heart rate varied between 70 and 90 beats.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness due to the presence of generalized bifrontal spike and wave discharges and a focal left frontal spike and wave discharge.
CLINICAL IMPRESSION:  The presence of bifrontal generalized spike-wave discharges may suggest an idiopathic generalized epilepsy in this patient.  The appearance of a focal spike in the left frontal region may suggest fragmentation of the generalized pattern during drowsiness but may also suggest the concomitant appearance of a generalized process plus a localized process, such as may be seen in __________ epilepsy or possibly in generalized epilepsy with febrile seizures plus (GEFS+).  Clinical correlation is advised.

INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with an anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while lethargic.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontal central beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  Overall the background is of low amplitude consistent with delta slowing at 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of less than 20 microvolts seen continuously.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at C44/F4 seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
Focal slow waves seen continuously at C44/F4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts with additional asymmetric increased amplitude and faster frequencies consistent with a breach.
SEIZURES:  Throughout the recording, there were about 6 seizures which appeared to have an electrographic onset, sometimes at O2 and at times at C4 beginning with high-frequency beta discharge that could again start on the occipital region or the central region and increase in frequency and then in amplitude, later to slow down in frequency but increase in amplitude and would spread either from the occipital region towards the central region at C4 or from the central region to the occipital region and continue to evolve.  They would last for about 1 minute to 2 minutes.  Clinically, the patient appears to open his eyes and roll his eyes towards the right and may have some twitching of his arm and mouth movements.  The tech did question him once and he remained unresponsive.
HEART RATE:  120s between seizures and 134 while having a seizure.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to recurrent seizures as well as right central focal slowing and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of status epilepticus with multiple seizures arising either from the right occipital or central region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral, structural cerebral dysfunction and irritability over the right central and frontal region.  These findings were discussed with the primary team as soon as the EEG was read.  Long-term EEG will be performed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 39-year-old right-handed gentleman who presents with history of generalized tonic-clonic seizures.  Past medical history is significant for posttraumatic epilepsy and HIV infection.
MEDICATIONS:  Versed at and Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the bedside using standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulations are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, there is a slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm consisting of 7-7.5 Hz frequency activity.  There is excess 5-6 Hz theta activity during short periods of wakefulness.  There is low amplitude, generalized beta activity throughout the recording.  There are almost continuous bifrontal sharply contoured delta activity with a frequency of 2-3.5 Hz.  At times associated with occasional sharp and slow wave activity with no evolution.  There is also almost continuous delta activity noted in right temporal region.  Stage 1 sleep was seen as evidenced by vertex waves and posts.  Stage 2 sleep was seen as evidenced by sleep spindles and K complexes.  The heart rate was 80 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background and posterior dominant rhythm.
Bifrontal slowing almost continuously with sharply contoured configurations.
Occasional bifrontal sharp and slow waves activities with no evolution.
Right temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing and slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm are suggestive of metabolic toxic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  Continuous slowing of bifrontal region is consistent with structural lesions in these regions.  The presence of sharp and slow waves is suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity.  Continuous slowing of temporal region is also consistent with a structural lesions in this area.  Generalized beta activity could be due to the effect of sedating medications including benzodiazepine or barbiturate or it can be seen in anxiety or hyperthyroidism.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No seizures were captured during this recording.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 70-year-old woman found on the floor on April 9, drowsy, not following commands, agitated,  intubated with a low grade fever.
MEDICATIONS:  Coumadin, midazolam, fentanyl, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent, but intermittently arouses and bites the endotracheal tube.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow, poorly organized and lacks some of the typical morphologies of an awake individual.  The patient has intermittent arousals with the suggestion of a 7-8 Hz alpha rhythm.  Shifting asymmetries were noted.  In addition, intermittent attenuations were noted.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an arousal response.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Shifting slowing.
Intermittent attenuations.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are nonspecific, but are most supportive of a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy or other diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  If epilepsy is an important consideration a repeat tracing when the patient is extubated may be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 77-year-old male admitted for syncope.  The patient collapsed while walking to the bathroom and had PEA code for 8 minutes on April 10, now with jerking movements.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, imipenem.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The initial EEG is markedly slow, low voltage and suppressed with low voltage delta and smaller amounts of theta.  There is some variability in the initial sections of the record with a bit more theta.  Spontaneous arousals were noted with an increase in higher amplitude theta frequency activity.
Intermittent involuntary jerking of the lower extremities was recorded without ictal change.
Occasional eye movements were noted without evidence of arousal.
On one occasion but on a second occasion eye movements were associated with an increase in higher amplitude theta frequency activity.  During that section, involuntary jerk artifact was noted but no epileptiform features were seen.
Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
A low voltage pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is more characteristic of a chronic than an acute encephalopathy.  In this individual with a history of severe anoxic injury, there is some variability.  The myoclonic jerks were not associated with an EEG change.  To place this EEG in the appropriate prognostic context, a bit more information about the events in January 2013 and April 2013 would be necessary.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old male with hypertension, renal failure, diabetes.  Past history of MVA while intoxicated, admitted in early March with right subdural hematoma requiring right craniectomy.  The patient experienced 1 seizure since discharge from the hospital.  This is a repeat EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, isosorbide, Norvasc, gabapentin, lisinopril, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed, but hyperventilation was deferred.  A right craniotomy defect was noted.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In relaxed wakefulness, the background EEG is low-to-medium amplitude with a 6 Hz alpha rhythm which is a bit more prominent on the right than the left.  Bursts of shifting slowing were noted with sharply contoured delta with a broad field of spread in the right temporal region, but also right central parietal region.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, snore artifact was noted and snoring functioned as an arousal for this individual.  Following snoring, the patient was waking up with an actually a faster alpha rhythm of 7.5 Hz.
Photic stimulation did not significantly active the record.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Shifting slowing.
Focal slowing in the right hemisphere which may be maximum at T4, the right parietal region or right temporal region.
Breach rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The background slowing is a nonspecific findings which can be seen in diffuse disturbance of cerebral function which may include significant head trauma, renal failure or other metabolic issues. This patient appears to be excessively sleepy and in fact, snoring produced an alerting response for this individual. Evaluation of this patient's neuro anatomy as well as other causes for hypersomnolence with important, given the prominent snore arousals. In comparison to the March 20, 2013, EEG, the focal slowing from the right has improved.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 67-year-old male with post traumatic epilepsy, admitted with repetitive seizures and prolonged postictal delirium.  The family states that the patient usually has a postictal right hemiparesis.  Past history of significant traumatic brain injury.  The patient states that he does not take his seizure medication.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Just prior to the EEG, the patient was quite somnolent, but he became more awake as the EEG began.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is diffusely slow with primarily a theta pattern.  There is an asymmetry noted, initially with a bit slower theta-delta on the left and a bit faster frequency activity of theta on the right.  The patient drifts in and out of a drowsy state.  He is not able to cooperate with hyperventilation.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is some sharply contoured slowing noted in the right anterior temporal region.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.  Heart rate 90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Excess theta.
An asymmetry with a slower background on the left.
Rare sharply contoured slowing in the right frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This patient with a history of traumatic brain injury and  asymmetry described above may be related to both the parenchymal pathology and the injury to the cranium.  No seizures were recorded.  Of note, the patient was a bit more awake at the end of the EEG, compatible with a resolving postictal state.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 54-year-old female with history of hypertension, CHF, and status post cardiac pacemaker who presents for seizure-like activity occurred about a month ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Spiriva, simvastatin, aspirin, levothyroxine, lisinopril, lorazepam, Zanaflex, and isosorbide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 8.5-9 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6.5-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in a driving response.  Heart rate was 80 beats per minute with pacemaker rhythm.
IMPRESSION:  This is this is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen during wakefulness.  There is no epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or a 24-hour ambulatory EEG may be helpful.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This was predominantly drowsiness and stage 1 sleep record with brief periods of wakefulness.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonisamide, albuterol, Zyrtec.
TECHNICAL PROBLEMS:  The C3 CZ leads appear to have been closely placed because of which there is flattening of EEG in that channel.
HISTORY:  A 27-year-old lady who is mentally challenged, born out of complicated pregnancy, i.e. cesarean section and was born blue.  She was diagnosed with seizure disorder 1 year ago.  Per mother the patient has seizures every day with just eye twitching.  Also has left-sided twitching.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Periods of wakefulness were very brief as this was predominantly a sleep record.  In the brief period that the was awake there is diffuse slowing with a posterior dominant rhythm in the theta range with maximum frequency of 7 Hertz which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.
Sleep was characterized by diffuse slowing and some waves resembling vertex waves, but no definite vertex morphology was seen.  There were abnormal discharges seen during sleep which will be further described below under the section abnormal discharges.
Hypoventilation did not change the record significantly.
Photic stimulation did not elicit any abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized symmetric frontally predominant spike and wave activity of 2.5 Hertz frequency and 130 to 150 microvolt amplitude were noted mainly during drowsiness and sleep.
There was generalized diffuse slowing in the theta range.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Frontally predominant generalized symmetric 2.5 Hertz spike and wave discharges in sleep.
Symmetric diffuse slowing in the theta range.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with that of a diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy with a pattern consistent with Lennox-Gastaut syndrome.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 48-year-old lady who presented with acute respiratory distress.  The patient remained unresponsive, even after discontinuation of the fentanyl, for which an EEG was obtained.
MEDICATIONS:  Cefepime.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1-channel EKG.  Sleep and wakefulness were captured.  Activation procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG opens to a diffusely slow background in the delta range with a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and an amplitude of 30 to 50 microvolts.  There is excess beta in the frontal leads.
The EEG is reactive to stimuli. There are clear state changes with some normal sleep elements which included occasional spindles.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:
Diffuse slowing with 2 to 4 Hz frequency and 30 to 50 microvolts amplitude.
Frontally predominant triphasic waves seen frequently.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse delta range slowing.
Frontally predominant triphasic waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is non specific with regards to etiology. However, the presence of triphasic waves suggests that this may be due at least in part to metabolic dysfunction causing diffuse encephalopathy.  The presence of excess beta indicates that there might also be a component of medication-induced encephalopathy.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 84-year-old woman with posttraumatic epilepsy after MVA at age 11.  The patient recalls blackout spells, tonic-clonic seizures and occasional myoclonic jerks.  Epilepsy now pretty well controlled, seizure-free for a year, but with dementia and atherosclerosis.  Previously evaluated for status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, Risperdal, donepezil, simvastatin, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation are performed.  Hyperventilation was not possible.  This is an awake and asleep record.
TECHNICAL:  No significant issues.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The overall background in maximal wakefulness includes a glimpse of a 9 HZ rhythm but with generous data.  Focal slowing is noted, most particularly in the left mid temporal region with some rhythmic and arrhythmic mixed theta delta in the left temporal region.  In addition, in wakefulness, there are discrete left temporal sharp waves as well as TIRDA.  There is also some shifting slowing noted from the right hemisphere.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements, attenuation of the alpha rhythm, and more significant bursts of focal slowing on the left.  The patient was transitioned in and out of a drowsy state with an increase in beta.
Photic stimulation elicited a level that is driving response.
Heart rate 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal focal slowing.
Left temporal discrete sharp waves.
Left temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
Background slowing and disorganization.
Occasional bursts of slowing in contralateral hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is similar to a previous study which identified seizures from the left, but the overall background is, of course, markedly improved as the patient had not been in status epilepticus recently.
Overall, this EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy on the left, but there are bihemispheric features which may represent age-related changes or bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Nearly 21 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old man who was found down on the floor unresponsive with a finger stick of 25.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Zosyn, vancomycin, sildenafil.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed at patient's bedside.  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1/T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of periods of diffuse voltage attenuation lasting from several seconds to approximately 12-15 seconds, followed by progressive onset of bifrontal slow delta activity that increases in frequency and amplitude and spreads diffusely.  These episodes occur throughout the recording.  When the patient is stimulated diffuse voltage attenuation was achieved.  Due to the recurrent nature of these episodes, I suspect that these represent recurrent seizures.  No abnormal sleep architecture is captured.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
FINDINGS:  Status epilepticus.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 21-minute EEG due to suspected status epilepticus involving bifrontal regions.  However, at least on several occasions, during the recording this discrete EEG pattern could be elicited by stimulation.  Therefore, it is also possible that these episodes represent forms of reactivity.  The findings were communicated to the neurology consult team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 58-year-old male, found down on the 14th with profound hypoglycemia, areas of skin breakdown, rhabdomyolysis, and persistently unresponsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vimpat, lisinopril, vancomycin, Zosyn, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive.
TECHNICAL:  This patient was in isolation due to fomites.  Consequently, the EEG machine was placed some distance from the patient and gloving and gowning was necessary to stimulate the patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal and includes rhythmic delta with FIRDA.  There are occasional triphasic waves noted in the EEG as well as shifting slowing.  Intermittent attenuations were noted.
Tactile stimulation of the patient on some occasions produced an alerting response with eye movement.  On some but not all occasions, tactile stimulation clearly reduced the FIRDA.  There is a handful of left frontal sharp waves noted in the record.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a markedly slow pattern.
FIRDA.
Triphasic waves.
Intermittent attenuations.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  A toxic or metabolic process or a deep brain stem process may contribute to this.  No clinical seizures were noted.  In contrast to the previous EEG, this patient was
not as responsive to tactile stimulation, but there was certainly evidence of responsivity and variability.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 34-year-old male with past history of right-sided numbness, seizures, stroke, HIV, schizophrenia, borderline personality.  Patient now had episodes occurring 8 to 10 times a week with dizziness, loss of consciousness, tonic clonic activity and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Risperdal, Advair, aspirin, Epzicom, Prezista and Viread.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized with a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Central MU activity was noted, but testing was not performed to confirm this.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record, producing some shifting slowing.   As hyperventilation continued, a burst of high amplitude rhythmic slowing from the left frontal region was identified.  No clinical correlates were noted.  This discharge was approximately 19 seconds in duration.  Of note, the burst of rhythmic slowing on the left seems to end over about 5 seconds and then a relatively normal awake pattern was noted.
In relaxed wakefulness, there is a mild degree of background slowing and as the patient transitions to drowsiness, there is very subtle underlying delta in the left hemisphere compared to the right.
Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was awake.  Although there was a driving response, the photic stimulation seems to accentuate some underlying focal slowing at T5.
Heart rate:  66 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Mild background disorganization in wakefulness.
Subtle focal slowing from the left.
Left posterior temporal slowing in photic.
Electrographic left hemisphere seizure in hyperventilation without clinical correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a focal mechanism for seizures for this patient. Given the electrographic seizure identified above, the patient's referring neurologist will be contacted so that additional management may be implemented.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 73-year-old woman with previous bilateral strokes, baseline receptive aphasia, dialysis, and carotid endarterectomy.  The patient had an episode where she woke up a nap and had briefly slurred speech.  Over the course of her hospitalization, her language improved, although her comprehension did not.  Evaluate for seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Plavix, clonidine, and Ativan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was poorly cooperative.  This is primarily an awake record.
TECHNICAL:  The bedside record was with a fair amount of artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow, lacking some of the normal milestones in an awake adult.  In particular, there is scant if any alpha activity.  The overall pattern is a lower voltage theta pattern, relatively featureless with smaller amounts of delta.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:  The replacement of normal background with a relatively low voltage diffusely slow pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This is a somewhat technically challenging EEG in that there is a fair amount of muscle but no significant focal or epileptiform features were noted.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 71-year-old man with a history of a stroke, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, CHF, gout and anxiety who presents with right upper extremity shaking for 15 minutes, then right hand weakness with a previous left MCA and pontine stroke, as well as bilateral basal ganglia strokes.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Seroquel, aspirin, Diovan, carvedilol, mirtazapine, Crestor, Protonix, heparin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead electrocardiogram electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontocentral beta.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen occasionally at F7/T3 while in wakefulness and drowsiness.
Focal slow waves seen intermittently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  84.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left anterior temporal sharp waves and focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related to epilepsy with seizures possibly arising from the left frontotemporal region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontotemporal region, which may be due to a known stroke.  No seizures were seen.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 21-year-old woman with a history of seizures.  She has been seizure free since 2010.  She was diagnosed with lupus approximately 1-1/2 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine, and prednisone.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to a standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.   Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  During maximal wakefulness, the posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 10.5 to 11 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep, posterior dominant rhythm attenuates, bursts of centrally pronounced theta as well as diffuse delta are captured.  There are frequent multifocal epileptiform discharges.  They occur independently over the bitemporal regions with face reversal over T3 and T4 electrodes.  They also occur in moderate to high amplitudes 0.5 to 2 second runs of generalized frontocentral predominant spikes with __________slow waves.  The__________runs have either right or left-sided lead in and they are often poorly formed.  Hyperventilation is produced with fair effort and produces no significant change in the background.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetric occipital driving with multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
Epileptiform discharges found independently over bitemporal regions, with face reversal over T3 and T4 electrodes, as well as 0.5 to 2 second bursts of poorly formed, broadly based approximately 8.5 Hz generalized spike and wave discharges, that are more pronounced frontocentrally.
No electrographic seizures.  No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and drowsy EEG due to multifocal epileptiform discharges.  This finding could indicate multiple epileptogenic foci, however, __________could also be seen in __________generalized epilepsy of a patient who is taking an anti-epileptic medication.  No electrographic seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Intractable seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 27-year-old woman with a history of mental retardation due to a complicated pregnancy and hypoxia during birth with recurrent refractory seizures, here for differential.
MEDICATIONS:  Zonegran and albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 7-8 Hz and appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  Overall, the background is slow and does not have normal organization and has intermittent bursts of generalized spike and wave, which I will describe in the abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded only during wakefulness.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Bursts of slow spike and wave with anterior predominance and symmetric onset lasting for up to 10 seconds with no clinical correlate seen at 2 to 2.5 Hz intermittently.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen continuously throughout the recording.
HEART RATE:  72.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bursts of slow generalized spike and wave and diffuse slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of symptomatic generalized epilepsy.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 39-year-old woman with a past medical history of seizures and history of sarcoidosis, neurosarcoidosis, diabetes, obstructive sleep apnea, gastroparesis, and stroke, admitted for seizures on April 12, 2013, readmitted on April 17, 2013, now for followup seizures, now increased to one every 2 to 3 days.  Last seizure on June 15, 2013.
MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, citalopram, Plavix, Tylenol, lisinopril, Norvasc, Mepron, Imuran, prednisone, milk of magnesia, Lipitor, Dilaudid, Flexeril, NovoLog, aspirin, atenolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures included photic stimulation, which produced no abnormal discharges.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
Abnormal discharges:  Focal slow waves seen intermittently at F7/T3 and at times at F8/T4, occasionally a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz and amplitude of 20 to 40 microvolts.
Heart rate:  80.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to bilateral anterior temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

DATE OF THE RECORDING:  07/09/2013 from approximately 7:00 p.m. until 07/10/2013 at approximately 8:00 a.m.  Total length of the recording is approximately 7 hours, since the patient was disconnected from the system from approximately 2:00 a.m. until approximately 8:00 a.m.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 42-year-old man with a history of seizures since childhood, who now presents with increase in seizure frequency.  Seizures are characterized by change in mental status lasting approximately 10-20 seconds.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol and Depakote.
CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single lead EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The recording was performed continuously.  The recording was reviewed several times during the recording period.  The patient was equipped with an event button.  Pushbutton events were reviewed.  Medication staff notes and technician notes were reviewed as well.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude theta and delta activity.  Periods of sleep are brief and are characterized by symmetrical sleep spindles.  No electrographic seizures were captured.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing and disorganization.
No electrographic seizures.  Brief fragmented sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 7-hour continuous audio-video EEG recording due to moderate diffuse slowing and disorganization.  This finding indicates diffuse cerebral dysfunction that is etiologically nonspecific.  No electrographic seizures were captured.  These findings were conveyed to the neurology primary team.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Twenty-five minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 42-year-old man who seizures since childhood, who now presents with increase in seizure frequency.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Depakote, and Ativan given at an outside emergency room.
CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single lead EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of polymorphic low to moderate amplitude diffuse theta admixed with occasional delta.  During sleep, the degree of delta increases.  Brief bifrontal fast activity is captured.  A single electrographic seizure is captured.  Clinically, it occurs out of sleep when the technologist wakes up the patient for hyperventilation.  During the seizure, the patient does not respond and appears to have possible right hand systemic posturing.  Electrographically, there is rapid diffuse voltage attenuation and appearance of diffuse fast activity that is most pronounced bifrontally.  The seizure lasts approximately 35-40 seconds.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort and does not result in significant change in the background.  Photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Mild to moderate diffuse slowing.
Occasional bifrontal brief fast activity.
A single clinical and electrographic seizure out of wakefulness of unclear lateralization, possibly bifrontal in onset.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 25-minute awake and asleep EEG due to mild to moderate diffuse slowing, bifrontal fast activity that is likely to be epileptiform in nature, and a single approximately 40 second seizure out of sleep of unclear lateralization, possibly frontal in onset.  Diffuse slowing indicates nonspecific cerebral dysfunction.   Epileptiform discharges and seizure indicate near cortical origin of the patient's epilepsy.  These findings were conveyed to the neurology primary team at the time of the review.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 40-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy and anxiety disorder, recent hospitalization for repetitive seizures from the right temporal region.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote and Xanax.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  The recording began when the patient was drowsy but she was able to follow commands.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is diffusely slow with more of a theta pattern.  In addition, there is intermittent focal slowing from the right mid to posterior temporal region.
Hyperventilation was performed early in the record producing bursts of rhythmic frontal delta, as well as accentuating the focal slowing.  The patient transitions into stage 2 sleep with spindles.  In stage 2 sleep, there is some shifting slowing in the temporal regions.
Photic stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting off to sleep and did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate: 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
A pattern of rhythmic background slowing.
Superimposed arrhythmic slowing in the right mid to posterior temporal region.
A handful of shifting bursts of shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The marked background slowing is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in a postictal state but does support a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  In comparison to previous EEGs, less epileptiform activity was noted.  The
focal slowing in the right temporal region is ipsilateral to the previous epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 67-year-old man with multiple breakthrough seizures, followed by prolonged postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  This EEG captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-8 Hz in frequency, well formed on the left side and is disrupted at times on the right side.  It is seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is diffuse excess theta activity during wakefulness in 6-7 Hz.  There is breach rhythm seen at the left mid and posterior temporal with raised sharp waves with no evolution.  There are bursts of right temporal slowing with a frequency of 5-6 Hz.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and further slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  Heart rate is 70 beats per minutes and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
Excess diffuse theta during wakefulness.
Right temporal slowing during wakefulness.
Rare sharp waves seen arising from the left temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Breach rhythm is consistent with patient's history of right craniotomy.  Left temporal slowing seen at the right hemisphere is suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality in the subcortical white matter of the right hemisphere.  The sharp waves seen arising from the left temporal region is suggestive of epileptogenicity of the right temporal region.  Diffuse slowing is consistent with mild to moderate encephalopathy due to toxic, metabolic, degenerative, or postictal state.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
